ong anti-extradition bill protests}}\n[[File:Yuen Long Station White Tee people oepn the gate 20190721.png|thumb|Mob opening the gate in Yuen Long Station concourse]]\n[[File:Nam Pin Wai people 20190722.png|thumb|Overnight, the mobsters in Nam Pin Wai Village]]\nThe '''2019 Yuen Long attack''' was a mob attack that occurred on 21 to 22 July 2019, in [[Yuen Long]], Hong Kong.<ref name=\"smcp-2019-07-22a2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019657/hong-kong-police-chief-defends-officers-arriving-35|title=Hong Kong police chief defends officers arriving 35 minutes after first reports of Yuen Long mob violence against protesters and MTR passengers|last1=Leung|first1=Christy|date=22 July 2019|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=23 July 2019|last2=Ting|first2=Victor|location=Hong Kong|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722201232/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019657/hong-kong-police-chief-defends-officers-arriving-35|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Prodemocracy201907222\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=131719&sid=4|title=Pan-dems accuse police of collusion with Yuen Long triads|date=22 July 2019|newspaper=The Standard|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=Sing Tao News Corporation|location=Hong Kong}}</ref><ref name=\"ny-2019-07-222\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/world/asia/hong-kong-protest-mob-attack-yuen-long.html|title=Mob Attack at Hong Kong Train Station Heightens Seething Tensions in City|date=22 July 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722121506/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/world/asia/hong-kong-protest-mob-attack-yuen-long.html|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An armed mob of over 100 men dressed in white indiscriminately attacked civilians on streets with steel rods and [[rattan]] canes and attacked passengers in the [[Yuen Long station|Yuen Long MTR station]]<ref name=\"guardian-2019-07-222\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/22/where-were-the-police-hong-kong-outcry-after-masked-thugs-launch-attack|title='Where were the police?' Hong Kong outcry after masked thugs launch attack|date=22 July 2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722033537/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/22/where-were-the-police-hong-kong-outcry-after-masked-thugs-launch-attack|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cna-2019-07-222\">{{cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/hong-kong-yuen-long-mtr-station-masked-men-injured-11741980|title=45 injured after mob attack at Hong Kong MTR station|date=22 July 2019|accessdate=23 July 2019|publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723060922/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/hong-kong-yuen-long-mtr-station-masked-men-injured-11741980|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> including the elderly, children,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019669/how-marauding-gang-struck-fear-yuen-long-leaving-pregnant|title=How marauding gang dressed in white struck fear into Yuen Long|date=23 July 2019|newspaper=South China Morning Post|accessdate=23 July 2019|location=Hong Kong|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723000416/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019669/how-marauding-gang-struck-fear-yuen-long-leaving-pregnant|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> black-clad protesters,<ref name=\":2\"/> journalists and lawmakers.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/just-chaos-bloodshed-hong-kong-district-hundreds-masked-men-assault-protesters-journalists-residents/|title=Chaos and bloodshed in Hong Kong district as hundreds of masked men assault protesters, journalists, residents|last=Cheng|first=Kris|date=22 July 2019|website=Hong Kong Free Press (HKFP)|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722221221/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/just-chaos-bloodshed-hong-kong-district-hundreds-masked-men-assault-protesters-journalists-residents/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At least 45 people were injured in the incident,<ref name=\":42\">[https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019524/least-10-injured-baton-wielding-mob-suspected-triad At least 45 injured as rod-wielding mob dressed in white rampages through Yuen Long MTR station, beating screaming protesters] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722221837/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019524/least-10-injured-baton-wielding-mob-suspected-triad |date=22 July 2019 }} \u2013 ''South China Morning Post''</ref> including a pregnant woman.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u8972\u64ca\u3011\u767d\u88d9\u5973\u61f7\u5b55\u4e0d\u8db33\u500b\u6708\u6c92\u901a\u77e5\u91ab\u9662\u3000\u8a3a\u6240\u6c42\u91ab\u8b49\u80ce\u5e73\u5b89 (22:46)|url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E/article/20190723/s00001/1563890883621/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E7%99%BD%E8%A3%99%E5%A5%B3%E6%87%B7%E5%AD%95%E4%B8%8D%E8%B6%B33%E5%80%8B%E6%9C%88%E6%B2%92%E9%80%9A%E7%9F%A5%E9%86%AB%E9%99%A2-%E8%A8%BA%E6%89%80%E6%B1%82%E9%86%AB%E8%AD%89%E8%83%8E%E5%B9%B3%E5%AE%89|department=online \"instant news\"|newspaper=Ming Pao|publisher=Media Chinese International|location=Hong Kong|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724015415/https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E/article/20190723/s00001/1563890883621/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E7%99%BD%E8%A3%99%E5%A5%B3%E6%87%B7%E5%AD%95%E4%B8%8D%E8%B6%B33%E5%80%8B%E6%9C%88%E6%B2%92%E9%80%9A%E7%9F%A5%E9%86%AB%E9%99%A2-%E8%A8%BA%E6%89%80%E6%B1%82%E9%86%AB%E8%AD%89%E8%83%8E%E5%B9%B3%E5%AE%89|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The attack happened following an [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|anti-extradition bill protest]] in [[Sheung Wan]], Hong Kong.\n\nDespite thousands of reports made to the [[999 (emergency telephone number)|999 emergency hotline]],<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{cite web |last1=Mahtani |first1=Shibani |last2=Shih |first2=Gerry |title=Hong Kong protesters occupy airport amid fears of escalating violence |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/hong-kong-protesters-occupy-airport-taking-message-to-visitors/2019/07/26/f4b2ea62-af6b-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726194102/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/hong-kong-protesters-occupy-airport-taking-message-to-visitors/2019/07/26/f4b2ea62-af6b-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |archive-date=26 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> the police did not arrive for more than 30 minutes and finally arrived one minute after the mob had left the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theinitium.com/article/20190723-hongkong-yuenlong-incident-timeline/ |title=\u5143\u6717\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u8972\u64ca\u4e8b\u4ef6\u91cd\u7d44\uff1a\u8b66\u5bdf\u5728\u767d\u8863\u4eba\u96e2\u958b\u4e00\u5206\u9418\u5f8c\u5230\u5834 \u2013 \u7aef\u50b3\u5a92 \u2013 23 July 2019  |access-date=23 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915073217/https://theinitium.com/article/20190723-hongkong-yuenlong-incident-timeline/ |archive-date=15 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|script-title=zh:\u6e2f\u9435\u7a31\u5831\u8b66\u5f8c\u8b66\u54e1\u300c\u90fd\u6709\u6bb5\u6642\u9593\u300d\u624d\u5230\u5143\u6717\u7ad9 \u2013 RTHK|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1469670-20190722.htm?|accessdate=22 July 2019|publisher=RTHK|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722043736/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1469670-20190722.htm|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E7%AB%99%E6%83%A1%E7%85%9E%E6%89%8B%E6%8C%81%E6%9C%A8%E6%A3%92%E6%89%93%E4%BA%BA-%E5%B8%82%E6%B0%91%E8%A8%98%E8%80%85%E8%A2%AB%E8%BF%BD%E6%89%93%E5%8F%97%E5%82%B7-%E6%9C%AA%E8%A6%8B%E8%AD%A6%E5%93%A1%E5%9F%B7%E6%B3%95/|title=\u3010\u7747\u7247\u3011\u5143\u6717\u7ad9\u60e1\u715e\u6728\u68d2\u6253\u4eba \u300a\u7acb\u5834\u300b\u8a18\u8005\u5e02\u6c11\u88ab\u8ffd\u6253\u53d7\u50b7 \u4e8b\u767c\u534a\u5c0f\u6642\u672a\u898b\u8b66\u54e1\u57f7\u6cd5 \u2013 \u7acb\u5834\u5831\u9053 \u2013 \u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e|newspaper=The Stand News|access-date=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721220857/https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E7%AB%99%E6%83%A1%E7%85%9E%E6%89%8B%E6%8C%81%E6%9C%A8%E6%A3%92%E6%89%93%E4%BA%BA-%E5%B8%82%E6%B0%91%E8%A8%98%E8%80%85%E8%A2%AB%E8%BF%BD%E6%89%93%E5%8F%97%E5%82%B7-%E6%9C%AA%E8%A6%8B%E8%AD%A6%E5%93%A1%E5%9F%B7%E6%B3%95/|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live|language=zh-hk}}</ref> No arrests were made that night. Many accused the police of failing to protect citizens from being attacked, with some even alleging that the police colluded with the mobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/21/breaking-hong-kong-police-deploy-tear-gas-protesters-govt-slams-direct-challenge-national-sovereignty/|title=Hong Kong police deploy tear gas, rubber bullets against protesters as gov't slams 'direct challenge to national sovereignty'|last=Press|first=Hong Kong Free|date=21 July 2019|website=Hong Kong Free Press (HKFP)|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722221225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/21/breaking-hong-kong-police-deploy-tear-gas-protesters-govt-slams-direct-challenge-national-sovereignty/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n{{More|2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|List of July 2019 Hong Kong protests}}\n[[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|Protests]] against the controversial [[2019 Hong Kong extradition bill|extradition bill]] had been going on since March. Recent demonstrations had turned into clashes, with the police allegedly using increasingly violent strategies and force on the protesters. Government supporters who favoured the extradition bill praised police as defenders of law and order. In contrast with the black dress code of government protesters, government supporters wore white. People dressed in white vandalised the [[Lennon Wall (Hong Kong)|Tai Po Lennon Wall]] on 19 July and participated in a demonstration showing solidarity with the police on 20 July.\n\nOn Sunday 21 July, the [[Civil Human Rights Front]] organised [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests#CHRF march|a protest]] from [[Causeway Bay]] to [[Wan Chai]] on Hong Kong Island, with black being the dress code again. Claiming to \"defend\" their homeland, the white-shirt mob warned all anti-extradition bill protesters not to set foot in Yuen Long.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469620-20190722.htm?|title=Suspected triads had warned of Yuen Long attacks|publisher=RTHK|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722144643/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469620-20190722.htm|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Attack ==\n{{external media| float = left| width = 230px| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RtfZeC8ltfs Footage of the 2019 Yuen Long attack] (SCMP)}}\n\nIn the evening, assailants wearing white shirts and armed with iron bars and wooden clubs gathered in [[Yuen Long Town, Hong Kong|Yuen Long]], a town in the New Territories. At around 10&nbsp;pm, these assailants started indiscriminately attacking people and cars on the street. They were reportedly targeting those wearing black, the dress code for the democracy rally on Hong Kong Island, but also attacked journalists and bystanders.<ref name=\"rthk20190721\">{{cite news|url=https://gbcode.rthk.hk/TuniS/news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469591-20190721.htm|title=Yuen Long MTR Station closed after violent attacks|date=21 July 2019|accessdate=21 July 2019|publisher=RTHK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721170057/https://gbcode.rthk.hk/TuniS/news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469591-20190721.htm|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcchinese20190722\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/chinese-news-49070742|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u5143\u6717\u767d\u8863\u4eba\u66b4\u8972\u8a18\u8005\u5e73\u6c11\u5f15\u773e\u6012\uff0c\u8b66\u65b9\u5426\u8a8d\u7e31\u5bb9\u52fe\u7d50\u300c\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\u300d|last=\u6797|first=\u7956\u5049|date=22 July 2019|accessdate=22 July 2019|work=BBC Chinese|language=zh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915073228/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/trad/chinese-news-49070742|archive-date=15 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> One pregnant woman, wearing a long white dress, was found lying on the floor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019669/how-marauding-gang-struck-fear-yuen-long-leaving-pregnant|title=How marauding gang struck fear into Yuen Long, leaving dozens of protesters and passengers injured, and Hong Kong police defending their response|last=Lam|first=Jeffie|date=23 July 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723000416/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019669/how-marauding-gang-struck-fear-yuen-long-leaving-pregnant|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt around 10:30&nbsp;pm, about a hundred white-shirted assailants appeared at [[Yuen Long railway station]] and attacked commuters in the concourse indiscriminately, on the platform and inside train compartments.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2196807/%E7%99%BD%E8%A1%A3%E4%BA%BA%E8%A5%BF%E9%90%B5%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E7%AB%99%E5%85%A7%E8%BF%BD%E6%89%93%E4%B9%98%E5%AE%A2+%E6%9E%97%E5%8D%93%E5%BB%B7%E5%98%B4%E8%A7%92%E5%8F%97%E5%82%B7%E6%B5%81%E8%A1%80|date=21 July 2019|newspaper=Hong Kong Economic Journal|access-date=21 July 2019|department=\"instant news\" section|language=zh-hk|script-title=zh:\u767d\u8863\u4eba\u897f\u9435\u5143\u6717\u7ad9\u5167\u8ffd\u6253\u4e58\u5ba2 \u6797\u5353\u5ef7\u5634\u89d2\u53d7\u50b7\u6d41\u8840|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721170010/https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2196807/%E7%99%BD%E8%A1%A3%E4%BA%BA%E8%A5%BF%E9%90%B5%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E7%AB%99%E5%85%A7%E8%BF%BD%E6%89%93%E4%B9%98%E5%AE%A2+%E6%9E%97%E5%8D%93%E5%BB%B7%E5%98%B4%E8%A7%92%E5%8F%97%E5%82%B7%E6%B5%81%E8%A1%80|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp-colluded-20190722\">{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019574/hong-kong-police-deny-accusation-they-colluded-thugs-who|title=Hong Kong police deny accusation they colluded with thugs who attacked passengers at train station, as one lawmaker calls incident 'terrorism'|last=Tsang|first=Denise|date=22 July 2019|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=22 July 2019|last2=Ting|first2=Victor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722072813/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019574/hong-kong-police-deny-accusation-they-colluded-thugs-who|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Two police officers arrived at 10:52&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"bbcchinese20190722\" /> However, they left the station as they judged that they were outnumbered by the assailants<ref name=\"scmp-colluded-20190722\" /> and did not have sufficient gear, according to the police.<ref name=\"scmp-raids\">{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019637/hong-kong-police-launch-raids-white-clad-thugs|title=Hong Kong police to launch raids on white-clad thugs, including members of 14K and Wo Shing Wo triad gangs, who unleashed terror on protesters and bystanders in Yuen Long|last=Lo|first=Clifford|date=22 July 2019|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722121906/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019637/hong-kong-police-launch-raids-white-clad-thugs|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Thirty police officers arrived at the station at 11:20&nbsp;pm, but the assailants had left.<ref name=\"scmp-raids\" /> Due to the violence, trains bypassed Yuen Long station between 10:56&nbsp;pm and 11:19&nbsp;pm,<ref name=\"Nampinwai\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019524/least-10-injured-baton-wielding-mob-suspected-triad|title=At least 36 injured as rod-wielding mob dressed in white rampages through Yuen Long MTR station, beating screaming protesters|last=Lam|first=Jeffie|date=22 July 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722031707/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019524/least-10-injured-baton-wielding-mob-suspected-triad|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the station was ordered closed at 11:55&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"rthk20190721\" /> However, after midnight, white-shirted assailants forced open the station's shutters to launch a second wave of attacks on passengers; no police officers were at the scene then.<ref name=\"scmp-raids\" /> In all, at least 45 citizens were reported injured,<ref name=\"45 people injured\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019534/hong-kong-gradually-returns-normal-after-another-night|title=Hong Kong gradually returns to normal after another night of violent extradition bill protests|last=Wong|first=Michelle|date=22 July 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722022823/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019534/hong-kong-gradually-returns-normal-after-another-night|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> including Legislative Council member [[Lam Cheuk-ting]] and two reporters; one other journalist had their equipment smashed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49066982|title=Hong Kong protests: Armed mob storms Yuen Long station|date=21 July 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=21 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722052058/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49066982|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"free press yuen long2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/just-chaos-bloodshed-hong-kong-district-hundreds-masked-men-assault-protesters-journalists-residents/|title=Chaos and bloodshed in Hong Kong district as hundreds of masked men assault protesters, journalists, residents|last=Cheng|first=Kris|date=22 July 2019|website=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=21 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721164910/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/just-chaos-bloodshed-hong-kong-district-hundreds-masked-men-assault-protesters-journalists-residents/|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCitizens made calls to the emergency hotline upon seeing the armed group assembling at around 7:00&nbsp;pm, and an MTR spokesman said the first call by the MTR to the police was made at around 10:45&nbsp;pm, but police officers arrived more than three hours after initial calls for help were made.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E6%94%BF%E6%83%85/354598/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97yoho%E8%A1%97%E5%9D%8A%E5%8F%97%E9%A9%9A%E4%B8%89%E5%B0%8F%E6%99%82-%E8%87%B4%E9%9B%BB%E8%AD%A6%E7%BD%B2-%E9%A9%9A%E4%BD%A0%E5%B0%B1%E5%94%94%E5%A5%BD%E5%87%BA%E8%A1%97|date=21 July 2019|accessdate=21 July 2019|publisher=Hong Kong 01|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c\u3011\u5143\u6717YOHO\u8857\u574a\u53d7\u9a5a\u4e09\u5c0f\u6642\u3000\u81f4\u96fb\u8b66\u7f72\uff1a\u9a5a\u4f60\u5c31\u5514\u597d\u51fa\u8857|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721170101/https://www.hk01.com/%E6%94%BF%E6%83%85/354598/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97yoho%E8%A1%97%E5%9D%8A%E5%8F%97%E9%A9%9A%E4%B8%89%E5%B0%8F%E6%99%82-%E8%87%B4%E9%9B%BB%E8%AD%A6%E7%BD%B2-%E9%A9%9A%E4%BD%A0%E5%B0%B1%E5%94%94%E5%A5%BD%E5%87%BA%E8%A1%97|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/354591/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-%E7%99%BD%E8%A1%A3%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E7%AB%99%E8%81%9A%E9%9B%86-%E8%BF%BD%E6%89%93%E5%B8%82%E6%B0%91%E5%89%8D%E5%A4%95-%E5%85%A9%E8%BB%8D%E8%A3%9D%E8%AD%A6%E8%BD%89%E8%BA%AB%E9%9B%A2%E5%8E%BB|date=21 July 2019|accessdate=21 July 2019|publisher=Hong Kong 01|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c\u3011\u767d\u8863\u4eba\u5143\u6717\u7ad9\u805a\u96c6\u3000\u8ffd\u6253\u5e02\u6c11\u524d\u5915\u3000\u5169\u8ecd\u88dd\u8b66\u8f49\u8eab\u96e2\u53bb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721170105/https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/354591/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-%E7%99%BD%E8%A1%A3%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E7%AB%99%E8%81%9A%E9%9B%86-%E8%BF%BD%E6%89%93%E5%B8%82%E6%B0%91%E5%89%8D%E5%A4%95-%E5%85%A9%E8%BB%8D%E8%A3%9D%E8%AD%A6%E8%BD%89%E8%BA%AB%E9%9B%A2%E5%8E%BB|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The local police call centre received thousands of calls between 10&nbsp;pm and midnight,<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/><ref name=\"scmp-defends-20190722\">{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019657/hong-kong-police-chief-defends-officers-arriving-35|title=Hong Kong police chief defends officers arriving 35 minutes after first reports of Yuen Long mob violence against protesters and MTR passengers|last=Leung|first=Christy|date=22 July 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=22 July 2019|last2=Ting|first2=Victor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722143813/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019657/hong-kong-police-chief-defends-officers-arriving-35|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and some citizens could not connect to the reporting hotline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/servants-triads-hong-kong-democrats-claim-police-condoned-mob-attacks-yuen-long/|title='Servants of triads': Hong Kong democrats claim police condoned mob attacks in Yuen Long|last=Chan|first=Holmes|date=22 July 2019|work=Hong Kong Free Press|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722090927/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/servants-triads-hong-kong-democrats-claim-police-condoned-mob-attacks-yuen-long/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The management of [[Yoho Mall]], a shopping mall next to Yuen Long station, also attempted to call the police but they could not get in touch with them.<ref name=\"45 people injured\" /> The police station near Yuen Long shut its gate in response to the hundreds that turned up to report the incident.<ref name=\"scmp-defends-20190722\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://coconuts.co/hongkong/news/chaos-and-bloodshed-36-in-hospital-after-men-in-white-shirts-brutally-attack-protesters-journalists-and-residents-in-yuen-long/|title=Chaos and Bloodshed: 36 in hospital after thugs brutally attack protesters, journos in Yuen Long (VIDEOS)|date=22 July 2019|work=[[Coconuts Media]]|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722094630/https://coconuts.co/hongkong/news/chaos-and-bloodshed-36-in-hospital-after-men-in-white-shirts-brutally-attack-protesters-journalists-and-residents-in-yuen-long/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Overnight, the police confronted the mobsters in [[Yuen Long Kau Hui|Nam Pin Wai Village]] and confiscated several steel bars,<ref name=\"Nampinwai\" /> though no arrests were made as they saw no one holding weapons and \"noticed nothing criminal\" in the village<ref name=\"Nampinwai\" /> and claimed they could not determine the identity of the white-shirted mobsters.<ref name=\"Yuen Long House of Rep\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/hong-kong-police-made-no-arrests-mob-assaulted-commuters-protesters-journalists-yuen-long/|title=Hong Kong police made no arrests after mob assaulted commuters, protesters, journalists in Yuen Long|last=Cheng|first=Kris|date=22 July 2019|work=Hong Kong Free Press|accessdate=22 July 2019|quote=Meanwhile, US House Representative Jim McGovern, a co-chair of the Congressional Executive-Commission on China, condemned the \"orchestrated violence against peaceful protesters\" as unacceptable.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722025922/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/hong-kong-police-made-no-arrests-mob-assaulted-commuters-protesters-journalists-yuen-long/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism of police's response ==\n[[File:\u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e\u8a18\u8005\u88ab\u8972\u64ca\u4e00\u523b.gif|thumb|The moment that a female journalist of [[Stand News]] was attacked by Chan (\u9673\u5fd7\u7965).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/344052192346676/posts/2395606480524560 |title=\u8b49\u64da\u78ba\u947f \u2013 \u5c0f\u725b\u8fb2\u5834\u8ca0\u8cac\u4eba\u9673\u5fd7\u7965\u8972\u64ca\u7acb\u5834\u8a18\u8005 |access-date=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817005839/https://www.facebook.com/344052192346676/posts/2395606480524560 |archive-date=17 August 2019 |url-status=live }}{{Primary source inline|date=October 2019}}</ref> Chan, has yet to be arrested by the police.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u5143\u6717\u6050\u8972\u5169\u500b\u6708 \u5e02\u6c11\u5f62\u9ede\u5546\u5834\u5167\u975c\u5750 {{!}} \u7368\u5a92\u5831\u5c0e|url=https://www.inmediahk.net/node/1067375|accessdate=18 October 2019|work=\u9999\u6e2f\u7368\u7acb\u5a92\u9ad4\u7db2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924044550/https://www.inmediahk.net/node/1067375|archive-date=24 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\n{{See also|Reputation and controversies of Hong Kong Police#Yuen Long attack|Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests}}\n\n=== Late arrival ===\nAn MTR spokesman said workers at the station saw disputes taking place at about 10:45&nbsp;pm and immediately contacted police within two minutes.<ref name=\"ny-2019-07-22\">{{cite news |title=Mob Attack at Hong Kong Train Station Heightens Seething Tensions in City |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/world/asia/hong-kong-protest-mob-attack-yuen-long.html |accessdate=23 July 2019 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722121506/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/world/asia/hong-kong-protest-mob-attack-yuen-long.html |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the police officers only arrived at around 11:15&nbsp;pm, when the mob was gone, despite receiving many other citizens' call to 999 for help.<ref name=\":5\" /> Residents also reported being ignored and treated rudely by 999 responders, who claimed they \"should stay at home if they are afraid\". Upon arrival, police were surrounded by dozens of angry residents and protesters who accused police of deliberately retreating after being called to the scene for the first assault.<ref name=\":42\"/>\n\nPolice Commander Li Hon-man, who was interviewed at the scene by journalists, was asked why police had arrived late. He was recorded on video saying \"I don't know if we were late\" and claimed to not have looked at his watch. Police said later that dealing with the concurrent anti-government protests on Hong Kong Island had stretched their resources.<ref name = \"scmp_3047028\">{{cite web |title=Hong Kong protests: Yuen Long mob attack victims sue police force |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3047028/hong-kong-protests-yuen-long-mob-attack-victims-sue-police/ |website=[[SCMP]] |accessdate=22 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121110725/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3047028/hong-kong-protests-yuen-long-mob-attack-victims-sue-police/ |archive-date=21 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThe following day, contact information for commanding officer Li Hon-man had been removed from the government directory, along with removal of the details for 11 other lower-ranking officers from the Yuen Long Division.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Incredible Shrinking Directory: Cops' details vanish from official site after Yuen Long |url=https://coconuts.co/hongkong/news/the-incredible-shrinking-directory-cops-details-vanish-from-official-site-after-yuen-long/ |website=Coconuts Hong Kong |accessdate=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725232253/https://coconuts.co/hongkong/news/the-incredible-shrinking-directory-cops-details-vanish-from-official-site-after-yuen-long/ |archive-date=25 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Kris |title=Name of Hong Kong police commander handling Yuen Long attacks removed from public gov't contact list |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/23/name-hong-kong-police-commander-handling-yuen-long-attacks-removed-public-govt-contact-list/ |website=Hong Kong Free Press |accessdate=25 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724184203/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/23/name-hong-kong-police-commander-handling-yuen-long-attacks-removed-public-govt-contact-list/ |archive-date=24 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, leaked videos show that two police officers had arrived on the scene but then turned away.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%e8%a6%81%e8%81%9e/article/20190723/s00001/1563820629982/%e5%85%83%e6%9c%97%e8%a5%b2%e6%93%8a%e6%8b%986%e4%ba%ba-%e8%ad%a6%e8%a2%ab%e8%b3%aa%e7%96%91%e6%94%be%e7%99%bd%e8%a1%a3-%e5%a0%b1%e6%a1%8835%e5%88%86%e9%90%98%e6%89%8d%e6%94%af%e6%8f%b4-%e7%9b%a7%e5%81%89%e8%81%b0%e5%90%a6%e8%aa%8d%e3%80%8c%e8%ad%a6%e9%bb%91%e5%90%88%e8%ac%80%e3%80%8d|script-title=zh:\u5143\u6717\u8972\u64ca\u62d86\u4eba \u8b66\u88ab\u8cea\u7591\u653e\u767d\u8863 \u5831\u684835\u5206\u9418\u624d\u652f\u63f4 \u76e7\u5049\u8070\u5426\u8a8d\u300c\u8b66\u9ed1\u5408\u8b00\u300d|newspaper=Ming Pao|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=Media Chinese International|location=Hong Kong|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915073221/https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A6%81%E8%81%9E/article/20190723/s00001/1563820629982/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E6%8B%986%E4%BA%BA-%E8%AD%A6%E8%A2%AB%E8%B3%AA%E7%96%91%E6%94%BE%E7%99%BD%E8%A1%A3-%E5%A0%B1%E6%A1%8835%E5%88%86%E9%90%98%E6%89%8D%E6%94%AF%E6%8F%B4-%E7%9B%A7%E5%81%89%E8%81%B0%E5%90%A6%E8%AA%8D%E3%80%8C%E8%AD%A6%E9%BB%91%E5%90%88%E8%AC%80%E3%80%8D|archive-date=15 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Police responded that the two policemen had backed off and called for help as they considered that they did not have the equipment to deal with armed crowds.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Shutting nearby police station ===\n\nMany also criticised the fact that police stations in the vicinity of the Yuen Long attacks shut their doors, despite a large group of residents who were there to report crimes. Police replied that the shut-down was for safety reasons due to large groups of protesters surrounding the stations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019657/hong-kong-police-chief-defends-officers-arriving-35|title=Police chief defends 'late' force response to mob violence in Yuen Long|date=22 July 2019|location=Hong Kong|access-date=23 July 2019|newspaper=South China Morning Post|first1=Christy|last1=Leung|first2=Victor|last2=Ting|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722201232/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3019657/hong-kong-police-chief-defends-officers-arriving-35|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Apprehending suspects===\nAfter blocking entrances to the area for more than three hours, the police made no arrests.<ref name=\":42\"/> When queried, the police explained that it could not be confirmed that those in white were the ones who participated in the violence and that the police were unable to record the identities of those in white because of their large numbers.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/hong-kong-police-made-no-arrests-mob-assaulted-commuters-protesters-journalists-yuen-long/|title=Hong Kong police made no arrests after mob assaulted commuters, protesters, journalists in Yuen Long|last=Cheng|first=Kris|date=22 July 2019|website=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722224201/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/hong-kong-police-made-no-arrests-mob-assaulted-commuters-protesters-journalists-yuen-long/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Yau Nai-keung, the Assistant District Commander of Crime in Yuen Long, also stated that the colleagues did not see anyone holding weapons at the area at all.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSix men were arrested on 22 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong police arrest six men over Yuen Long rampage by weapon-wielding mob, after unprecedented night of violence following extradition protests|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019666/hong-kong-police-arrest-six-men-over-yuen-long-rampage|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|location=Hong Kong|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|first1=Tony|last1=Cheung|first2=Clifford|last2=Lo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722200520/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019666/hong-kong-police-arrest-six-men-over-yuen-long-rampage|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the police, one of the arrested suspects had a [[Triad (organized crime)|triad]] background.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=209900&sid=11|title=White terror grips Yuen Long|last=Wong |first=Stella |newspaper=The Standard|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=Sing Tao News Corporation}}</ref> Five more men were arrested on 23 July 2019.<ref name=11arrest>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1470064-20190723.htm|title=Five more arrested over Yuen Long attacks|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=RTHK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723163249/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1470064-20190723.htm|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 August, two men were charged and held without bail in relation to the Yuen Long attacks. Of the 30 people who have so far been arrested, some of whom have links to organised crime syndicates, only four individuals have been charged as suspects. Court hearings were scheduled to begin on 25 October.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two more charged with rioting, denied bail over Yuen Long attacks |url=https://coconuts.co/hongkong/news/two-more-charged-with-rioting-denied-bail-over-yuen-long-attacks/ |website=Coconuts Hong Kong |accessdate=27 August 2019 |date=27 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827050509/https://coconuts.co/hongkong/news/two-more-charged-with-rioting-denied-bail-over-yuen-long-attacks/ |archive-date=27 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Alleged collusion ===\nPro-democratic lawmaker [[Eddie Chu]] Hoi-dick, representing New Territories West, stated: \u201cPolice didn\u2019t show up while thugs rampaged through the station and attacked Yuen Long residents indiscriminately last night,\" stating that this meant there was \"clear collusion between police and the gangs.\u201d<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTriad gangsters were previously linked to attacks on democracy activists in [[Mong Kok]] during the 2014 Umbrella Movement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2019/07/22/world/asia/22reuters-hongkong-extradition.html|title=Triad Gangster Attack in Hong Kong After Night of Violent Protests: Lawmaker|date=22 July 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=22 July 2019|agency=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722075755/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2019/07/22/world/asia/22reuters-hongkong-extradition.html|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At that time, police were [[Umbrella Movement#Anti-Occupy attacks|similarly accused]] of not responding in a timely manner and criticised for allowing attacks to occur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2014/10/hong-kong-police-triads-infiltrated-occupy-movement/|title=Hong Kong Police: Triads Infiltrated Occupy Movement|last1=Tiezzi|first1=Shannon|website=The Diplomat|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722075755/https://thediplomat.com/2014/10/hong-kong-police-triads-infiltrated-occupy-movement/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLynette Ong, an Associate Professor of Political Science at the University of Toronto commented that:\n{{quote|This is not the first time thugs have been sent in to beat up protesters. This is more organised, suggesting they are becoming more daring, and the Hong Kong government or pro-Beijing officials are becoming more desperate to put the protests to rest... The underlying motive is quite similar \u2026 Sending in thugs is an option to evade responsibility. If you send thugs, it's almost impossible to trace, and you can't hold anyone accountable.<ref name=triad>{{cite news |title=Hong Kong: why thugs may be doing the government's work |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/22/why-hong-kong-thugs-may-be-doing-the-governments-work |accessdate=31 July 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=23 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730012420/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/22/why-hong-kong-thugs-may-be-doing-the-governments-work |archive-date=30 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\n=== Allegations of misconduct in public office ===\nStephen S.N. Char, [[barrister]] and former Chief Investigator of the [[Independent Commission Against Corruption (Hong Kong)|Independent Commission Against Corruption]], indicated that intentional negligence by police officers who refused to offer public services might have committed the offence of [[misconduct in public office]] under the common law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190725/20736871|title=\u5143\u6717\u6050\u8972 ICAC\u67e5\u8b66\u9ed1\u52fe\u7d50 \u524d\u8abf\u67e5\u54e1\uff1a\u5018\u8896\u624b\u65c1\u89c0 \u8b66\u968a\u4e0a\u4e0b\u7686\u7006\u8077|website=Apple Daily|language=zh|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725040242/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190725/20736871|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 January 2020, eight people injured in the attack, including lawmaker Lam Cheuk-ting, announced\nthat they had filed a lawsuit against the police force, demanding 2.7 million Hong Kong dollars in compensation; Lam stated that the lawsuit had been filed to seek \"justice for the victims and for Hong Kong\".<ref name=\"scmp_3047028\"/>\n\n== Suspected involvement of Junius Ho ==\nAfter the incident, pro-Beijing legislator [[Junius Ho]] was accused of supporting the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190722/59848508|date=21 July 2019|newspaper=Apple Daily|access-date=21 July 2019|publisher=Next Digital|department=\"real time news\" section|location=Hong Kong|language=zh-hk|script-title=zh:\u3010\u7121\u8b66\u6642\u4efd\u3011\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u5411\u5143\u6717\u767d\u8863\u4eba\u9f13\u638c\u8c4e\u62c7\u6307\uff1a\u4f60\u54cb\u4fc2\u6211\u5605\u82f1\u96c4|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721172526/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190722/59848508|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In various videos posted online, Ho greeted the white-clothed group of assailants, shaking their hands and calling the suspected gangsters \"heroes\", giving them thumbs-up and saying to them \"thank you for your hard work.\" At least one of the white-clothed men who shook hands with Ho has been shown to have been inside Yuen Long Station during the attacks.<ref name=\"free press yuen long2\"/>\n\nHo later explained that he lived in Yuen Long and was merely passing by after dinner and agreed to greet one of his supporters who requested to take photos with him.<ref name=\":1\" /> Ho said he did not know anything about the attack when greeting them, and the meeting was before the incident. However, he also defended the mob at a press conference by saying that the incidents were a \"normal reaction to protesters who brought violence to the peaceful community after they stormed the liaison office\" and also praised them for \"safeguarding\" their district.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=131702&sid=4|title=Junius Ho accused of supporting Yuen Long mob|website=The Standard|access-date=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012085131/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=131702&sid=4|archive-date=12 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019621/pro-beijing-lawmaker-junius-ho-defends-white-clad-mob|title=Yuen Long attackers were defending their home, says lawmaker|date=22 July 2019|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722230440/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019621/pro-beijing-lawmaker-junius-ho-defends-white-clad-mob|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Law Society, of which Ho was once president, said it had received \"quite a number of complaints\" and is \"seriously looking into\" calls for disciplinary action against Ho and \"conducting reviews on relevant complaints, and will pass the matter to the Solicitors Disciplinary Tribunal if necessary.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nJunius Ho would later go on to lose his District Council seat in the [[2019 Hong Kong local elections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/24/hong-kong-residents-turn-up-for-local-elections-in-record-numbers|title=Hong Kong voters deliver landslide victory for pro-democracy campaigners|date=25 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\nMany shops on the streets and in shopping malls were closed in Yuen Long and the neighbouring towns Tuen Mun, Tin Shui Wai and Tsuen Wan on 22 July 2019.<ref name=\"thestandard0723\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=209900&sid=11|title= White terror grips Yuen Long  |date=23 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|newspaper=The Standard}}</ref> Rumours spread online warned that there would be more violence on that day. Many companies allowed employees who live in the districts to leave work early that day.<ref name=\":6\" /> Some schools in the district cancelled their afternoon activities.<ref name=\"thestandard0723\"/> Leisure and cultural facilities in Yuen Long operated by government closed early out of public safety considerations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/|title=Leisure and Cultural Services Department \u5eb7\u6a02\u53ca\u6587\u5316\u4e8b\u52d9\u7f72|publisher=Government of Hong Kong|access-date=24 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713011006/https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/|archive-date=13 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJunius Ho's office in [[Tsuen Wan]] was vandalised by the protesters after the attack. A glass partition was broken, as well as leaving memo that \"suggested a link between the violent gangs that carried out the attack the previous day and the police force\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469792-20190722.htm|title=Junius Ho's Tsuen Wan office trashed by protesters|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=RTHK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723162608/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469792-20190722.htm|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Protesters also posted anti-government sticky notes on the exterior wall of his offices in Tin Shui Wai<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469977-20190723.htm|title=Protesters hit Tin Shui Wai office of Junius Ho|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=RTHK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723164035/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469977-20190723.htm|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and Tuen Mun.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20190724/00176_018.html|script-title=zh:\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u7236\u6bcd\u58b3\u5893\u8b70\u8fa6\u906d\u7834\u58de|date=24 July 2019|access-date=24 July 2019|newspaper=[[Oriental Daily News]]|location=Hong Kong|publisher=Oriental Press Group|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724031133/https://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20190724/00176_018.html|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of unknown also vandalised the graves of his parents in [[Tuen Mun]],<ref name=SCMPgrave>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019750/pro-beijing-lawmaker-junius-ho-storms-out-live-tv-interview|title=Hong Kong protest hate figure Junius Ho's parents' graves vandalised amid extradition bill anger|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|newspaper=South China Morning Post|location=Hong Kong|first1=Jeffie|last1=Lam|author2=Su Xinqi|first3=Victor|last3=Ting|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723081812/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019750/pro-beijing-lawmaker-junius-ho-storms-out-live-tv-interview|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/24/democrat-eddie-chu-calls-investigation-pro-beijing-lawmaker-junius-hos-alleged-role-yuen-long-mob-attacks/|title=Democrat Eddie Chu calls for investigation into pro-Beijing lawmaker Junius Ho's alleged role in Yuen Long mob attacks|date=24 July 2019|access-date=26 July 2019|publisher=Hong Kong Free Press (HKFP)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725153115/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/24/democrat-eddie-chu-calls-investigation-pro-beijing-lawmaker-junius-hos-alleged-role-yuen-long-mob-attacks/|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> vandals also left graffiti with words such as \"official-triad collusion\"<ref name=SCMPgrave/> and \"[[Wo Shing Wo|Shing Wo]]\" (a triad) near the graves, fuelling rumours regarding the background of the vandals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%e6%b8%af%e8%81%9e/article/20190724/s00002/1563907944777/%e9%9b%99%e8%a6%aa%e5%a2%b3%e5%a2%93%e8%a2%ab%e6%af%81-%e4%bd%95%e5%90%9b%e5%a0%af%e4%bf%83%e5%90%84%e6%96%b9%e3%80%8c%e5%81%9c%e5%96%87%e3%80%8d-%e5%a1%97%e9%b4%89%e7%a2%91%e6%96%b7-%e8%ad%a6%e5%88%97%e5%88%91%e6%af%81|script-title=zh:\u96d9\u89aa\u58b3\u5893\u88ab\u6bc1 \u4f55\u541b\u582f\u4fc3\u5404\u65b9\u300c\u505c\u5587\u300d \u5857\u9d09\u7891\u65b7 \u8b66\u5217\u5211\u6bc1|date=24 July 2019|access-date=24 July 2019|newspaper=Ming Pao|publisher=Media Chinese International|location=Hong Kong|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724194227/https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%e6%b8%af%e8%81%9e/article/20190724/s00002/1563907944777/%e9%9b%99%e8%a6%aa%e5%a2%b3%e5%a2%93%e8%a2%ab%e6%af%81-%e4%bd%95%e5%90%9b%e5%a0%af%e4%bf%83%e5%90%84%e6%96%b9%e3%80%8c%e5%81%9c%e5%96%87%e3%80%8d-%e5%a1%97%e9%b4%89%e7%a2%91%e6%96%b7-%e8%ad%a6%e5%88%97%e5%88%91%e6%af%81|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA news conference was held on 24 July by six people who were attacked and had decided to come forward with their stories. Several people in the group, including lawmaker Lam Cheuk-ting, stated they may appeal for financial compensation of damages in a court of law and file suite against the police and the MTR Corporation. Lam also said that his political party would assist any others who wish to press charges and seek redress.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lok-kei |first1=Sum |title='The whole car smelled of blood': Hong Kong victims describe brutal attack at Yuen Long MTR station; some may sue for damages |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019955/whole-car-smelled-blood-hong-kong-victims-describe-brutal |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725222538/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019955/whole-car-smelled-blood-hong-kong-victims-describe-brutal |archive-date=25 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Petitions for dismissing Junius Ho as the member of University Council ===\nIn the light of Ho's potential involvement, a number of student bodies and alumni associations had made a declaration condemning both his suspected support of the attack, and what they described as his hate speech which had damaged the image of Lingnan University. They also jointly requested Chief Executive [[Carrie Lam]] to dismiss Ho from the University Council.  The University issued a statement afterwards, in which it denied that there was any connection between the stance of University and the actions of Ho. The statement also highlighted the University's respect for freedom of speech.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u5dba\u5927\u5b78\u751f\u6821\u53cb\u806f\u7f72 \u4fc3\u7f77\u514d\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u6821\u8463\u8077\u4f4d \u5dba\u5927\uff1a\u5176\u8a00\u8ad6\u8207\u6821\u65b9\u7121\u95dc {{!}} \u7acb\u5834\u5831\u9053 {{!}} \u7acb\u5834\u65b0\u805e|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%B6%BA%E5%A4%A7%E5%AD%B8%E7%94%9F%E6%A0%A1%E5%8F%8B%E8%81%AF%E7%BD%B2-%E4%BF%83%E7%BD%B7%E5%85%8D%E4%BD%95%E5%90%9B%E5%A0%AF%E6%A0%A1%E8%91%A3%E8%81%B7%E4%BD%8D-%E5%B6%BA%E5%A4%A7-%E5%85%B6%E8%A8%80%E8%AB%96%E8%88%87%E6%A0%A1%E6%96%B9%E7%84%A1%E9%97%9C/|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=Stand News |language=zh|location=Hong Kong|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817031809/https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E5%B6%BA%E5%A4%A7%E5%AD%B8%E7%94%9F%E6%A0%A1%E5%8F%8B%E8%81%AF%E7%BD%B2-%E4%BF%83%E7%BD%B7%E5%85%8D%E4%BD%95%E5%90%9B%E5%A0%AF%E6%A0%A1%E8%91%A3%E8%81%B7%E4%BD%8D-%E5%B6%BA%E5%A4%A7-%E5%85%B6%E8%A8%80%E8%AB%96%E8%88%87%E6%A0%A1%E6%96%B9%E7%84%A1%E9%97%9C/|archive-date=17 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=\u3010\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c\u3011\u5dba\u5927\u8207\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u5272\u5e2d\uff1a\u5c0a\u91cd\u8a00\u8ad6\u81ea\u7531 \u4e0d\u4ee3\u8868\u6821\u65b9\u7acb\u5834|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u793e\u6703\u65b0\u805e/354959/\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c-\u5dba\u5927\u8207\u4f55\u541b\u582f\u5272\u5e2d-\u5c0a\u91cd\u8a00\u8ad6\u81ea\u7531-\u4e0d\u4ee3\u8868\u6821\u65b9\u7acb\u5834|accessdate=10 November 2019|date=22 July 2019|last=\u913a\u66c9\u658c|work=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915073450/https://www.hk01.com/%E7%A4%BE%E6%9C%83%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E/354959/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-%E5%B6%BA%E5%A4%A7%E8%88%87%E4%BD%95%E5%90%9B%E5%A0%AF%E5%89%B2%E5%B8%AD-%E5%B0%8A%E9%87%8D%E8%A8%80%E8%AB%96%E8%87%AA%E7%94%B1-%E4%B8%8D%E4%BB%A3%E8%A1%A8%E6%A0%A1%E6%96%B9%E7%AB%8B%E5%A0%B4|archive-date=15 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Reclaim Yuen Long protest ===\n\nProtests originally planned on 27 and 28 July in [[Hung Hom]]-[[To Kwa Wan]], [[Tseung Kwan O]] and [[Sai Wan|Hong Kong Islands West]] were rescheduled or postponed to make way for a Reclaim Yuen Long action on 27 July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190723/20735471|title=\u4e09\u5340\u8b93\u8def\u30007.27\u300c\u5149\u5fa9\u5143\u6717\u300d|date=23 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|newspaper=Apple Daily|location=Hong Kong|language=zh-hk|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723165635/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190723/20735471|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the police issued the Letter of Objection, saying the proposed anti-mob march might 'create serious obstruction to the roads and pose a danger to marchers', after receiving pressure from the rural groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/25/breaking-hong-kong-police-ban-yuen-long-protest-saturday/|title=Hong Kong police ban Saturday's Yuen Long protest against mob attacks|date=25 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|location=Hong Kong|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726201512/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/25/breaking-hong-kong-police-ban-yuen-long-protest-saturday/|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The applicant announced he would instead walk alone along the originally proposed route and urged people not to follow him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1470666-20190726.htm|title=Appeal against ban on Yuen Long rally rejected|date=26 July 2019|access-date=27 July 2019|publisher=RTHK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727130816/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1470666-20190726.htm|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the risk of committing the [[unlawful assembly#Hong Kong|unlawful assembly]] offence, tens of thousands of people, or 288,000 as the original march applicant estimated, turned up in the town. Many protesters marched on [[Castle Peak Road]]. The police fired [[tear gas]] in the evening, including near residential areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/27/hong-kong-yuen-long-fresh-clashes-triads|title=Hong Kong: police fire teargas as thousands march in Yuen Long|date=28 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728011748/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/27/hong-kong-yuen-long-fresh-clashes-triads|archive-date=28 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press-releases/hong-kong-police-attack-yuen-long-protesters-unacceptable|title=Hong Kong: police attack on Yuen Long protesters unacceptable|publisher=Amnesty International|date=27 July 2019|access-date=28 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728143548/https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press-releases/hong-kong-police-attack-yuen-long-protesters-unacceptable|archive-date=28 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The police insisted that the tear gas shot did not affect the seniors living in an elderly home nearby, though photos showed otherwise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1683024/police-have-fired-a-record-amount-of-tear-gas-in-hong-kong/|title=In Hong Kong, almost everyone, everywhere\u2014including pets\u2014is getting tear gassed|first=Mary|last=Hui|work=Quartz|date=8 August 2019|accessdate=10 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809180711/https://qz.com/1683024/police-have-fired-a-record-amount-of-tear-gas-in-hong-kong/|archive-date=9 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Starting from 5&nbsp;pm, the police fired canisters of tear gas upon protesters near [[Yuen Long Kau Hui|Sai Pin Wai village]] and Nam Pin Wai Village, while protesters hurled objects in return.<ref name=\"roof\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E7%AA%81%E7%99%BC/357036/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%81%8A%E8%A1%8C-%E6%B3%B0%E7%A5%A5%E8%A1%97-%E8%A5%BF%E9%82%8A%E5%9C%8D%E8%AD%A6%E6%B0%91%E6%B7%B7%E6%88%B0-%E5%82%AC%E6%B7%9A%E5%BD%88%E6%93%AC%E5%B0%84%E4%B8%8A%E6%B0%91%E5%B1%85%E7%B0%B7%E8%93%AC|title=\u3010\u5143\u6717\u904a\u884c\u3011\u6cf0\u7965\u8857\u3001\u897f\u908a\u570d\u8b66\u6c11\u6df7\u6230\u3000\u50ac\u6dda\u5f48\u64ec\u5c04\u4e0a\u6c11\u5c45\u7c37\u84ec|work=Hong Kong 01|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727145433/https://www.hk01.com/%E7%AA%81%E7%99%BC/357036/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%81%8A%E8%A1%8C-%E6%B3%B0%E7%A5%A5%E8%A1%97-%E8%A5%BF%E9%82%8A%E5%9C%8D%E8%AD%A6%E6%B0%91%E6%B7%B7%E6%88%B0-%E5%82%AC%E6%B7%9A%E5%BD%88%E6%93%AC%E5%B0%84%E4%B8%8A%E6%B0%91%E5%B1%85%E7%B0%B7%E8%93%AC|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/27/hong-kong-yuen-long-fresh-clashes-triads|title=Hong Kong: police fire teargas as thousands march in Yuen Long|first=Lily|last=Kuo|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727052049/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/27/hong-kong-yuen-long-fresh-clashes-triads|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E/article/20190727/s00001/1564230837844/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%81%8A%E8%A1%8C%E3%80%91%E5%9C%96%E8%BC%AF-%E5%82%AC%E6%B7%9A%E7%85%99%E7%80%B0%E6%BC%AB%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97|title=\u3010\u5143\u6717\u904a\u884c\u3011\u5716\u8f2f\uff1a\u50ac\u6dda\u7159\u7030\u6f2b\u5143\u6717 (21:20)|work=[[Ming Pao]]|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727171109/https://news.mingpao.com/ins/%25E6%25B8%25AF%25E8%2581%259E/article/20190727/s00001/1564230837844/%25E3%2580%2590%25E5%2585%2583%25E6%259C%2597%25E9%2581%258A%25E8%25A1%258C%25E3%2580%2591%25E5%259C%2596%25E8%25BC%25AF-%25E5%2582%25AC%25E6%25B7%259A%25E7%2585%2599%25E7%2580%25B0%25E6%25BC%25AB%25E5%2585%2583%25E6%259C%2597|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/27/reclaim-yuen-long-thousands-hongkongers-vent-anger-mob-attacks-defying-police-protest-ban/|title='Reclaim Yuen Long': Tear gas deployed as thousands vent anger over mob attacks, defying Hong Kong police protest ban|first=Jennifer|last=Creery|work=Hong Kong Free Press|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727090538/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/27/reclaim-yuen-long-thousands-hongkongers-vent-anger-mob-attacks-defying-police-protest-ban/|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> While [[MTR]] had arranged special trains in [[Long Ping station]] to help protesters to leave Yuen Long,<ref name=\"station clash\"/> riot police began dispersing protesters with more force around 7:30&nbsp;pm, using batons and rubber bullets.<ref name=\"guardian\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/27/hong-kong-police-fire-tear-gas-rubber-bullets-yuen-long-protesters-defy-ban-anti-triad-rally/|title=Hong Kong police fire tear gas, rubber bullets as 'anti-triad' protesters retreat to Yuen Long station|work=Hong Kong Free Press|date=19 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727132042/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/27/hong-kong-police-fire-tear-gas-rubber-bullets-yuen-long-protesters-defy-ban-anti-triad-rally/|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Protesters fleeing to [[Yuen Long station]] were followed by the [[Special Tactical Squad]], and a standoff occurred inside the station.<ref name=\"station clash\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3020340/knife-attack-yuen-long-tensions-mount-ahead-hong-kong|title=Few hundred remaining protesters clash with Hong Kong police inside Yuen Long MTR station|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727061824/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3020340/knife-attack-yuen-long-tensions-mount-ahead-hong-kong|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E6%94%BF%E6%83%85/356822/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%81%8A%E8%A1%8C-%E7%9B%B4%E6%92%AD-%E7%A4%BA%E5%A8%81%E8%80%85%E6%AD%A3%E6%92%A4%E9%9B%A2-%E9%80%9F%E9%BE%8D%E6%94%BB%E5%85%A5%E8%A5%BF%E9%90%B5%E7%AB%99-%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%BA%E9%A0%AD%E9%83%A8%E6%B5%81%E8%A1%80|title=\u3010\u5143\u6717\u904a\u884c\u30fb\u76f4\u64ad\u3011\u793a\u5a01\u8005\u6b63\u64a4\u96e2\u3000\u901f\u9f8d\u653b\u5165\u897f\u9435\u7ad9\u3000\u6709\u4eba\u982d\u90e8\u6d41\u8840|work=Hong Kong 01|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727143536/https://www.hk01.com/%E6%94%BF%E6%83%85/356822/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%81%8A%E8%A1%8C-%E7%9B%B4%E6%92%AD-%E7%A4%BA%E5%A8%81%E8%80%85%E6%AD%A3%E6%92%A4%E9%9B%A2-%E9%80%9F%E9%BE%8D%E6%94%BB%E5%85%A5%E8%A5%BF%E9%90%B5%E7%AB%99-%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%BA%E9%A0%AD%E9%83%A8%E6%B5%81%E8%A1%80|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the protest, a passenger car near [[Nam Pin Wai (Yuen Long)|Nam Pin Wai]] was vandalised by the protesters.<ref name=HKETcarvandal/> Several weapons were discovered in the car<ref name=HKETcarvandal>{{cite news|url=https://topick.hket.com/article/2412688/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E7%A4%BA%E5%A8%81%E8%80%85%E5%9C%A8%E5%8D%97%E9%82%8A%E5%9C%8D%E7%99%BC%E7%8F%BE%E8%BC%89%E6%9C%89%E8%97%A4%E6%A2%9D%E7%A7%81%E5%AE%B6%E8%BB%8A%E3%80%80%E8%BB%8A%E4%B8%BB%E7%82%BA%E9%9D%9E%E8%8F%AF%E8%A3%94%E7%94%B7%E5%AD%90?mtc=10016|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u8972\u64ca\u3011\u793a\u5a01\u8005\u5728\u5357\u908a\u570d\u767c\u73fe\u8f09\u6709\u85e4\u689d\u79c1\u5bb6\u8eca\u3000\u8eca\u4e3b\u70ba\u975e\u83ef\u88d4\u7537\u5b50\n|work=Topick|publisher=Hong Kong Economic Times Holdings|language=zh-hk|date=27 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=standhat>{{cite news|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/727-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97-%E5%BB%82%E5%85%A7%E6%94%BE%E7%BD%AE%E8%97%A4%E6%A2%9D-%E7%A7%81%E5%AE%B6%E8%BB%8A%E8%A2%AB%E6%AF%81-%E8%BB%8A%E5%B0%BE%E7%AE%B1%E8%97%8F%E6%A3%8D%E5%88%80%E5%A4%A7%E9%87%8F%E6%AD%A6%E5%99%A8/|script-title=zh:\u3010727 \u5143\u6717\u3011\u5ec2\u5167\u653e\u7f6e\u85e4\u689d\u3000\u79c1\u5bb6\u8eca\u88ab\u6bc1\u3000\u8eca\u5c3e\u7bb1\u85cf\u68cd\u5200\u5927\u91cf\u6b66\u5668|date=27 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019|newspaper=Stand News|location=Hong Kong|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728134952/https://thestandnews.com/politics/727-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97-%E5%BB%82%E5%85%A7%E6%94%BE%E7%BD%AE%E8%97%A4%E6%A2%9D-%E7%A7%81%E5%AE%B6%E8%BB%8A%E8%A2%AB%E6%AF%81-%E8%BB%8A%E5%B0%BE%E7%AE%B1%E8%97%8F%E6%A3%8D%E5%88%80%E5%A4%A7%E9%87%8F%E6%AD%A6%E5%99%A8/|archive-date=28 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> that looked the same as the weapons brandished by the white-shirted men in the 21 July attacks,<ref name=applehat>{{cite news|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190728/20738942|script-title=zh:\u6751\u53e3\u8eca\u8f1b\u85cf\u6728\u68cd\u3000\u8ecd\u5e3d\u3000\u65e5\u672c\u5200|location=Hong Kong|newspaper=Apple Daily|date=27 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019|publisher=Next Digital|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729060422/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/daily/article/20190728/20738942|archive-date=29 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as a hat that resembled the uniform of Mainland law enforcement.<ref name=standhat/><ref name=applehat/> On 28 July, police arrested the car owner for possession of weapons.<ref name=Mingpao>{{cite news|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%e8%a6%81%e8%81%9e/article/20190729/s00001/1564339070926/%e5%8d%97%e9%82%8a%e5%9c%8d%e7%a7%81%e5%ae%b6%e8%bb%8a%e8%97%8f%e5%88%80%e6%a3%8d-%e8%ad%a6%e6%8b%98%e9%9d%9e%e8%8f%af%e8%a3%94%e6%bc%a2|script-title=zh:\u5357\u908a\u570d\u79c1\u5bb6\u8eca\u85cf\u5200\u68cd \u8b66\u62d8\u975e\u83ef\u88d4\u6f22|date=29 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019|location=Hong Kong|newspaper=Ming Pao|publisher=Media Chinese International|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729054803/https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%25E8%25A6%2581%25E8%2581%259E/article/20190729/s00001/1564339070926/%25E5%258D%2597%25E9%2582%258A%25E5%259C%258D%25E7%25A7%2581%25E5%25AE%25B6%25E8%25BB%258A%25E8%2597%258F%25E5%2588%2580%25E6%25A3%258D-%25E8%25AD%25A6%25E6%258B%2598%25E9%259D%259E%25E8%258F%25AF%25E8%25A3%2594%25E6%25BC%25A2|archive-date=29 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Online rumoured the identity of a personal name that found on a bill inside the car, was connected to the [[Hong Kong Liaison Office|Liaison Office]], however, the Liaison Office denied.<ref name=Mingpao/>\n\n=== 21 August Yuen Long sit-in ===\n\nThousands of demonstrators staged a sit-in protest at Yuen Long station to demand justice and to remember the victims of the mob attacks that had occurred exactly one month prior on 21 July.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lam |first1=Jeffie |last2=Lok-kei |first2=Sum |last3=Mok |first3=Danny |title=Chaos at Hong Kong's Yuen Long MTR station as protesters confront police while marking one month since mob attack |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3023806/chaos-mtr-station-hong-kong-protesters-confront-police |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=22 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822013508/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3023806/chaos-mtr-station-hong-kong-protesters-confront-police |archive-date=22 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pomfret |first1=James |last2=Torode |first2=Greg |title=Hong Kong protesters clash with police, angry at lack of prosecutions after subway mob attack |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-hongkong-protests/hong-kong-protesters-clash-with-police-angry-at-lack-of-prosecutions-after-subway-mob-attack-idUKKCN1VB0OB |agency=Reuters |accessdate=22 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821214926/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-hongkong-protests/hong-kong-protesters-clash-with-police-angry-at-lack-of-prosecutions-after-subway-mob-attack-idUKKCN1VB0OB |archive-date=21 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Reaction==\nSeveral politicians such as [[Kenneth Leung]] Kai-cheong,<ref name=\"Prodemocracy201907222\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.inmediahk.net/node/1065882|script-title=zh:\u6c11\u4e3b\u6d3e\u8b74\u8cac\u5143\u6717\u6050\u8972 \u6279\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\u897f\u74b0\u653f\u5e9c\u806f\u624b\u6253\u58d3|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|language=zh-hk|newspaper=IN Media HK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722144532/http://www.inmediahk.net/node/1065882|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Roy Kwong]] Chun-yu<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019574/hong-kong-police-deny-accusation-they-colluded-thugs-who|title=Hong Kong police deny accusation they colluded with thugs who attacked passengers at train station, as one lawmaker calls incident 'terrorism'|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|newspaper=South China Morning Post|location=Hong Kong|first1=Denise|last1=Tsang|first2=Victor|last2=Ting|quote=\"Some said it was terrorism, I don't think that's an exaggeration at all,\" [Roy Kwong] said.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722153710/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019574/hong-kong-police-deny-accusation-they-colluded-thugs-who|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and other public figures<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E8%AC%9B%E6%B8%85%E6%A5%9A-%E6%98%AF-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2-%E4%B8%8D%E6%98%AF-%E8%A1%9D%E7%AA%81/|script-title=zh:\u8b1b\u6e05\u695a\uff1a\u662f\u300c\u5143\u6717\u6050\u8972\u300d\uff0c\u4e0d\u662f\u300c\u885d\u7a81\u300d|author=\u6881\u555f\u667a|department=Opinion section|newspaper=The Stand News|language=zh-hk|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722031658/https://thestandnews.com/politics/%E8%AC%9B%E6%B8%85%E6%A5%9A-%E6%98%AF-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2-%E4%B8%8D%E6%98%AF-%E8%A1%9D%E7%AA%81/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190722/59849879|script-title=zh: \u6c88\u65ed\u6689\u5f15\u570b\u969b\u6a19\u6e96 \u6307\u5143\u6717\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u6253\u4eba\u300c\u662f\u4e00\u5834\u6050\u8972\u300d|trans-title=Simon Shen pointed out that the event is indeed a terrorist attack according to the international standard|department=online \"realtime\" news|newspaper=Apple Daily|location=Hong Kong|publisher=Next Digital|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|url-access=subscription|language=zh-hk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722081739/https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/realtime/article/20190722/59849879|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thestandnews.com/politics/7-21-\u5143\u6717\u6050\u8972-\u6e05\u6d17\u820a\u7d44\u7e54-\u88cf\u653f\u6cbb-\u4e00\u570b\u5169\u5236\u7684\u4e16\u754c\u672b\u65e5/|script-title=zh:7.21 \u5143\u6717\u6050\u8972 \u2014 \u6e05\u6d17\u820a\u7d44\u7e54\u3001\u88cf\u653f\u6cbb\u3001\u4e00\u570b\u5169\u5236\u7684\u4e16\u754c\u672b\u65e5|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|language=zh-hk|newspaper=The Stand News|department=Opinion section|author=\u76e7\u65af\u9054|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722161207/https://thestandnews.com/politics/7-21-%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2-%E6%B8%85%E6%B4%97%E8%88%8A%E7%B5%84%E7%B9%94-%E8%A3%8F%E6%94%BF%E6%B2%BB-%E4%B8%80%E5%9C%8B%E5%85%A9%E5%88%B6%E7%9A%84%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C%E6%9C%AB%E6%97%A5/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> condemned the incident as a terrorist attack.\n\n''[[Hong Kong Economic Times]]'' compared the attack with two terrorist attacks in Mainland China in 2014, suggesting the Yuen Long attack may qualify as a terrorist attack according to the Mainland law.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.hket.com/article/2407535/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B5%E5%B9%B4%E5%89%8D%E5%85%A9%E5%AE%97%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2%20%E8%88%87%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E7%9B%B8%E4%BC%BC%E4%B9%8B%E8%99%95|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u8972\u64ca\u3011\u4e2d\u570b5\u5e74\u524d\u5169\u5b97\u6050\u8972 \u8207\u5143\u6717\u8972\u64ca\u76f8\u4f3c\u4e4b\u8655|department=\u5929\u4e0b\u4e86\u7136 column|newspaper=Hong Kong Economic Times|language=zh-hk|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915073225/https://inews.hket.com/article/2407535/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E4%B8%AD%E5%9C%8B5%E5%B9%B4%E5%89%8D%E5%85%A9%E5%AE%97%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2|archive-date=15 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The newspaper also compared the attack with U.S. law, making the same conclusion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.hket.com/article/2407474/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E6%98%AF%E5%90%A6%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2%EF%BC%9F%20%E4%B8%80%E6%96%87%E7%9C%8B%E6%87%82%E4%BF%9D%E9%9A%AA%E7%95%8C%E5%8F%8A%E7%BE%8E%E5%9C%8B%E5%8F%B8%E6%B3%95%E7%95%8C%E6%A8%99%E6%BA%96|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u8972\u64ca\u3011\u662f\u5426\u6050\u8972\uff1f \u4e00\u6587\u770b\u61c2\u4fdd\u96aa\u754c\u53ca\u7f8e\u570b\u53f8\u6cd5\u754c\u6a19\u6e96|department=\u5929\u4e0b\u4e86\u7136 column|newspaper=Hong Kong Economic Times|language=zh-hk|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723132928/https://inews.hket.com/article/2407474/%E3%80%90%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E8%A5%B2%E6%93%8A%E3%80%91%E6%98%AF%E5%90%A6%E6%81%90%E8%A5%B2%EF%BC%9F%20%E4%B8%80%E6%96%87%E7%9C%8B%E6%87%82%E4%BF%9D%E9%9A%AA%E7%95%8C%E5%8F%8A%E7%BE%8E%E5%9C%8B%E5%8F%B8%E6%B3%95%E7%95%8C%E6%A8%99%E6%BA%96|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nParties from both factions of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] (LegCo), condemned the violence of the attack. Pro-democratic councillors signed a petition to condemn the negligence of the police in allowing suspected [[Triad (organized crime)|triads]] to become enforcers of their own rules,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2196811/%E6%B0%91%E4%B8%BB%E6%B4%BE%E8%AD%B0%E5%93%A1%E8%81%AF%E7%BD%B2+%E5%BC%B7%E7%83%88%E8%AD%B4%E8%B2%AC%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E6%9A%B4%E8%A1%8C%E5%8F%8A%E8%AD%A6%E6%96%B9%E5%A4%B1%E8%81%B7|date=21 July 2019|newspaper=Hong Kong Economic Journal|access-date=21 July 2019|department=\"instant news\" section|language=zh-hk|script-title=zh:\u6c11\u4e3b\u6d3e\u8b70\u54e1\u806f\u7f72 \u5f37\u70c8\u8b74\u8cac\u5143\u6717\u66b4\u884c\u53ca\u8b66\u65b9\u5931\u8077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721173259/https://www2.hkej.com/instantnews/current/article/2196811/%25E6%25B0%2591%25E4%25B8%25BB%25E6%25B4%25BE%25E8%25AD%25B0%25E5%2593%25A1%25E8%2581%25AF%25E7%25BD%25B2%2B%25E5%25BC%25B7%25E7%2583%2588%25E8%25AD%25B4%25E8%25B2%25AC%25E5%2585%2583%25E6%259C%2597%25E6%259A%25B4%25E8%25A1%258C%25E5%258F%258A%25E8%25AD%25A6%25E6%2596%25B9%25E5%25A4%25B1%25E8%2581%25B7|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while the pro-Beijing [[Democratic Alliance for the Betterment and Progress of Hong Kong|DAB]] condemned the violent incident and \"demanded that the police follow up on [the attack] seriously\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469632-20190722.htm|title=Police failed to protect Yuen Long people|publisher=RTHK|date=21 July 2019|accessdate=22 July 2019|quote=demanded that the police follow up on this seriously.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722063600/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1469632-20190722.htm|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe injured, as well as LegCo Councillors [[Lam Cheuk-ting]] (who was also injured in the attack),<ref name=\"ny-2019-07-222\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-extradition/triad-gangster-attack-in-hong-kong-after-night-of-violent-protests-lawmaker-idUSKCN1UH02O|title=Hong Kong police criticized over failure to stop attacks on protesters|agency=Reuters|location=Hong Kong|date=22 July 2019|orig-year=updated 23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|first1=James|last1=Pomfret|first2=Donny|last2=Kwok|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722153416/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-extradition/triad-gangster-attack-in-hong-kong-after-night-of-violent-protests-lawmaker-idUSKCN1UH02O|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[James Tien (politician)|James Tien]],<ref name=\"ny-2019-07-222\"/> and a number of pro-democratic councillors<ref name=\"Prodemocracy201907222\"/> accused the mob of being members of triad gangs. The police also believed that some of the suspects arrested on 22 July \"had triad backgrounds\".<ref name=\"ny-2019-07-222\"/><ref name=\":6\"/>\n\nSome politicians, such as [[Zachary Wong]], Councillor of the [[Yuen Long District Council]], accused the mob of being under the influence of the Beijing central government, citing the opinion of a [[Hong Kong Liaison Office|Liaison Office]] official in an inauguration event of [[Shap Pat Heung]] Rural Committee days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A6%81%E8%81%9E/article/20190723/s00001/1563820638391/%E5%8D%80%E8%AD%B0%E5%93%A1-%E9%84%89%E4%BA%8B%E4%B8%AD%E4%BA%BA%E5%85%A9%E5%91%A8%E5%89%8D%E9%86%9E%E9%87%80-%E9%84%89%E5%B1%80%E8%AD%B4%E8%B2%AC%E6%9A%B4%E5%8A%9B|script-title=zh:\u5340\u8b70\u54e1\uff1a\u9109\u4e8b\u4e2d\u4eba\u5169\u5468\u524d\u919e\u91c0\u9109\u5c40\u8b74\u8cac\u66b4\u529b|newspaper=Ming Pao|publisher=Media Chinese International|location=Hong Kong|language=zh-hk|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723153810/https://news.mingpao.com/pns/%25E8%25A6%2581%25E8%2581%259E/article/20190723/s00001/1563820638391/%25E5%258D%2580%25E8%25AD%25B0%25E5%2593%25A1-%25E9%2584%2589%25E4%25BA%258B%25E4%25B8%25AD%25E4%25BA%25BA%25E5%2585%25A9%25E5%2591%25A8%25E5%2589%258D%25E9%2586%259E%25E9%2587%2580-%25E9%2584%2589%25E5%25B1%2580%25E8%25AD%25B4%25E8%25B2%25AC%25E6%259A%25B4%25E5%258A%259B|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the attack, [[Reuters]] also claimed that they had the audio recording of the speech of the official.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-extradition-gang-insight/chinese-official-urged-hong-kong-villagers-to-drive-off-protesters-before-violence-at-train-station-idUSKCN1UL0LK|title=Chinese official urged Hong Kong villagers to drive off protesters before violence at train station|date=26 July 2019|access-date=27 July 2019|agency=Reuters|first1=James|last1=Pomfret|first2=Greg|last2=Torode|first3=David|last3=Lague|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727011835/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-extradition-gang-insight/chinese-official-urged-hong-kong-villagers-to-drive-off-protesters-before-violence-at-train-station-idUSKCN1UL0LK|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJournalists' associations condemned the attacks on journalists as \"a severe infringement of press freedom\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=209905&story_id=50041376&d_str=20190723&sid=11|title=Accusations fly amidparty line on attacks|first=Cindy|last=Wan|work=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=23 July 2019|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{ill|Arthur Shek Kang Chuen|zh|\u77f3\u93e1\u6cc9}}, Vice-editor-in-chief of ''Hong Kong Economic Times'' and one of the executive directors of its publisher [[Hong Kong Economic Times Holdings]], resigned on 23 July after retracting his personal opinion on encouraging the use of violence on anti-bill protesters; he expressed the opinion during an event supporting police on 20 July, a day before the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.hket.com/article/2408528/%E7%9F%B3%E9%8F%A1%E6%B3%89%E8%BE%AD%E4%BB%BB%E7%B6%93%E6%BF%9F%E6%97%A5%E5%A0%B1%E5%89%AF%E7%A4%BE%E9%95%B7%E5%8F%8A%E9%9B%86%E5%9C%98%E5%9F%B7%E8%91%A3%20%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E7%94%9F%E6%95%88|script-title=zh:\u77f3\u93e1\u6cc9\u8fad\u4efb\u7d93\u6fdf\u65e5\u5831\u526f\u793e\u9577\u53ca\u96c6\u5718\u57f7\u8463 \u5373\u6642\u751f\u6548|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|newspaper=Hong Kong Economic Times|language=zh-hk|department=online \"instant news\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724163929/https://inews.hket.com/article/2408528/%E7%9F%B3%E9%8F%A1%E6%B3%89%E8%BE%AD%E4%BB%BB%E7%B6%93%E6%BF%9F%E6%97%A5%E5%A0%B1%E5%89%AF%E7%A4%BE%E9%95%B7%E5%8F%8A%E9%9B%86%E5%9C%98%E5%9F%B7%E8%91%A3%20%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E7%94%9F%E6%95%88|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere was backlash on 22 July when 30 protesters demonstrated at Yuen Long police station to condemn the attacks, the delayed police response, and the alleged collusion between police and triad gangs. Hundreds of social workers then marched to the same police station to report the violence, hand over criminal evidence and file complaints against the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019574/hong-kong-police-deny-accusation-they-colluded-thugs-who|title=Hong Kong police deny accusation they colluded with thugs who attacked passengers at train station, as one lawmaker calls incident 'terrorism'|first=Denise|last=Tsang|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=22 July 2019|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722072813/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3019574/hong-kong-police-deny-accusation-they-colluded-thugs-who|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E7%AA%81%E7%99%BC/354853/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-600%E7%A4%BE%E5%B7%A5%E9%9B%86%E9%AB%94%E5%A0%B1%E6%A1%88-%E5%9B%9B%E5%90%8D%E4%BB%A3%E8%A1%A8%E6%8F%90%E4%BA%A4%E5%85%89%E7%A2%9F%E4%BD%9C%E8%AD%89%E6%93%9A|script-title=zh:\u3010\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c\u3011600\u793e\u5de5\u96c6\u9ad4\u5831\u6848\u3000\u56db\u540d\u4ee3\u8868\u63d0\u4ea4\u5149\u789f\u4f5c\u8b49\u64da|work=Hong Kong 01|date=22 July 2019|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August, [[Labour Party (Hong Kong)|Labour Party]] representatives held a protest outside the Government offices demanding that Junius Ho be stripped of his title as a Justice of the Peace. Along with a petition of 20,000 signatures, the Labour Party chairman said Ho was unfit to hold the position as he had incited others to use violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1472081-20190802.htm?|title=Thousands demand Junius Ho lose JP title|publisher=RTHK|access-date=3 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803132940/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1472081-20190802.htm|archive-date=3 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Government response ===\nThe government condemned the attacks in a statement released after midnight local time.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201907/22/P2019072200025.htm|title=The Government strongly condemns violent acts|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=Hong Kong Government|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721202809/https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201907/22/P2019072200025.htm|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the government refused to categorise the attack as a riot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-49069602|script-title=zh:\u6797\u90d1\u6708\u5a25\u89c1\u8bb0\u8005\uff1a\u62d2\u7edd\u5b9a\u6027\u5143\u6717\u4e8b\u4ef6\u4e3a\u201c\u66b4\u52a8\u201d \u7edd\u4e0d\u8bb8\u89e6\u78b0\u201c\u4e00\u56fd\u4e24\u5236\u201d\u5e95\u7ebf|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|website=BBC News \u4e2d\u6587 (Chinese)|publisher=BBC|language=zh-hans|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723030713/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-49069602|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=mediasession>{{cite web|url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201907/22/P2019072200881.htm|script-title=zh:\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6703\u898b\u50b3\u5a92\u958b\u5834\u767c\u8a00\u548c\u7b54\u554f\u5167\u5bb9\uff08\u9644\u77ed\u7247\uff09|trans-title=Transcript of remarks by CE at media session (with video)|type=Transcript|publisher=Hong Kong Government|last=Lam|first=Carrie|others=journalists and other government officials also took part in the media session|language=zh-hk|date=22 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723093123/https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201907/22/P2019072200881.htm|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nChief Executive [[Carrie Lam]] held a media session at 3&nbsp;pm on 22 July 2019,<ref name=mediasession/> first condemning [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests#21 July march|protesters]] for besieging the [[Hong Kong Liaison Office|Liaison Office]] in Sheung Wan the night before. In addressing why she prioritised the liaison office incident before the Yuen Long mob attack in her remarks, Lam said: \"It's important that Hong Kong citizens' daily lives are protected, but I believe all citizens will agree that the successful implementation of [[one country, two systems]] is ... even the most important thing.\"<ref name=\"thestandard.com.hk\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=209899&story_id=50041370&con_type=1&d_str=20190723&sid=11|title=Lam dismisses accusations of collusion with Yuen Long thugs|last=Un|first=Phoenix|newspaper=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=23 July 2019|access-date=23 July 2019|publisher=Sing Tao News Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204320/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=209899&story_id=50041370&con_type=1&d_str=20190723&sid=11|archive-date=20 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLam did not directly address the media's questions about the alleged delayed response by police to calls for help.<ref name=\"thestandard.com.hk\"/> Lam ultimately condemned the organised attacks on protesters and bystanders, stating that \"violence will only breed more violence.\" However, former lawmaker [[James Tien (politician)|James Tien]] questioned her sincerity and asked if Triads were now ruling Hong Kong. In a Facebook post, he urged Lam to resign for what happened in Yuen Long that night.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramzy |first1=Austin |title=Mob Attack at Hong Kong Train Station Heightens Seething Tensions in City |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/world/asia/hong-kong-protest-mob-attack-yuen-long.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722121506/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/world/asia/hong-kong-protest-mob-attack-yuen-long.html |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Commissioner of Police [[Stephen Lo]] said he needed to follow up with the incident and refused to comment at this point on the police's reaction towards mobs in this incident compared to the high-pressure approach towards protesters in earlier situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u653f\u60c5/355031/\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c-\u88ab\u8cea\u554f-\u4f60\u6628\u665a\u53bb\u4e86\u54ea\u88cf-\u6797\u912d-\u8b74\u8cac-\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5168\u7d00\u9304|title=\u3010\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c\u3011\u88ab\u8cea\u554f\uff1a\u4f60\u6628\u665a\u53bb\u4e86\u54ea\u88cf\uff1f\u6797\u912d\u300c\u8b74\u8cac\u300d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5168\u7d00\u9304|last=\u6c99\u534a\u5c71|date=22 July 2019|website=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK|access-date=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724165620/https://www.hk01.com/%E6%94%BF%E6%83%85/355031/%E5%85%83%E6%9C%97%E9%BB%91%E5%A4%9C-%E8%A2%AB%E8%B3%AA%E5%95%8F-%E4%BD%A0%E6%98%A8%E6%99%9A%E5%8E%BB%E4%BA%86%E5%93%AA%E8%A3%8F-%E6%9E%97%E9%84%AD-%E8%AD%B4%E8%B2%AC-%E8%A8%98%E8%80%85%E6%9C%83%E5%85%A8%E7%B4%80%E9%8C%84|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July, Chief Secretary for Administration [[Matthew Cheung]] apologised to citizens and admitted that the police department's response fell short of public expectations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/26/hong-kongs-chief-sec-apologises-handling-yuen-long-attacks-stirring-dissent-police/|title=Hong Kong's chief sec. apologises over handling of Yuen Long attacks, stirring dissent from police|last=Chan|first=Holmes|publisher=Hong Kong Free Press (HKFP)|location=Hong Kong|date=26 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727162801/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/26/hong-kongs-chief-sec-apologises-handling-yuen-long-attacks-stirring-dissent-police/|archive-date=27 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Questioned about demands for an independent inquiry into police misconduct, Cheung said that the matter would be handled internally. Shortly after the apology, images of printed statements accompanied by warrant cards circulated on-line from dissenting police officers, questioning the need to apologise and calling Cheung an \"enemy of the police.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Holmes |title=Hong Kong's chief sec. apologises over handling of Yuen Long attacks, stirring dissent from police |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/26/hong-kongs-chief-sec-apologises-handling-yuen-long-attacks-stirring-dissent-police/ |website=Hong Kong Free Press |accessdate=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726151729/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/26/hong-kongs-chief-sec-apologises-handling-yuen-long-attacks-stirring-dissent-police/ |archive-date=26 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Police Inspectors' Association and the Junior Police Officers' Association expressed \"the most serious condemnation\" of his statement of apology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1470855-20190727.htm|title=Matthew Cheung says he 'totally supports' police|publisher=RTHK|location=Hong Kong|date=27 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728162205/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1470855-20190727.htm|archive-date=28 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n*United Kingdom \u2013 [[Andrew Murrison]], [[Minister of State]] at the UK's [[Department for International Development]], condemned the violence in a meeting of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], said \"I stand by people's right to protest peacefully and lawfully\" and \"[Britain] will be keeping a close eye on this.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/uk-will-keep-close-eye-on-hong-kong-violence-probe |title=Britain will keep 'close eye' on Hong Kong violence probe |date=23 July 2019 |access-date=24 July 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse |newspaper=The Straits Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723182522/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/uk-will-keep-close-eye-on-hong-kong-violence-probe |archive-date=23 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*United States \u2013 [[Jim McGovern (American politician)|Jim McGovern]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives|US House of Representatives]] and chair of the [[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]], described the attack as \"orchestrated violence against peaceful protesters\" and urged Hong Kong authorities to protect the [[demonstration (political)|freedom of demonstration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/hong-kong-police-made-no-arrests-mob-assaulted-commuters-protesters-journalists-yuen-long/|title=Hong Kong police made no arrests after mob assaulted commuters, protesters, journalists in Yuen Long|first=Kris|last=Cheng|publisher=Hong Kong Free Press (HKFP)|date=22 July 2019|accessdate=22 July 2019|quote=Meanwhile, US House Representative Jim McGovern, a co-chair of the Congressional Executive-Commission on China, condemned the \"orchestrated violence against peaceful protesters\" as unacceptable.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722025922/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/22/hong-kong-police-made-no-arrests-mob-assaulted-commuters-protesters-journalists-yuen-long/|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Japan \u2013 The Consulate-General of Japan in Hong Kong issued new warning to their expatriates in Hong Kong<ref>{{cite news |url=https://udn.com/news/story/120538/3948067 |script-title=zh:\u793a\u5a01\u4e0d\u65b7\uff01\u65e5\u672c\u3001\u5357\u97d3\u7b49\u570b\u5bb6\u5c0d\u9999\u6e2f\u767c\u51fa\u65c5\u904a\u8b66\u793a |agency=[[Central News Agency (Taiwan)|Central News Agency]] |newspaper=United Daily News |language=zh-tw |date=24 July 2019 |access-date=24 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724114835/https://udn.com/news/story/120538/3948067 |archive-date=24 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> regarding rumours of further attacks in the New Territories.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.hk.emb-japan.go.jp/itpr_ja/kougi_20190723.html|script-title=ja:\u9003\u4ea1\u72af\u7f6a\u4eba\u6761\u4f8b\u7b49\u6539\u6b63\u554f\u984c\u3092\u5de1\u308b\u6297\u8b70\u6d3b\u52d5\u3078\u306e\u6ce8\u610f\u559a\u8d77\uff08\u305d\u306e11\uff09|date=23 July 2019|access-date=24 July 2019|publisher=Consulate-General of Japan in Hong Kong|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724124550/https://www.hk.emb-japan.go.jp/itpr_ja/kougi_20190723.html|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Establishment of District Council task force==\nThe pro-democracy camp won a landslide victory in the [[2019 Hong Kong local elections]], held later in the year. The [[Yuen Long District Council]], previously dominated by pro-government councillors, also swung pro-democratic, with democrats taking 33 of the 39 elected seats and gaining control of the 45-seat council. The new council term commenced on 1 January 2020. On 7 January, the council passed a motion to establish a working group to investigate the mob attack.<ref name=\"councilors\">{{cite news |title=Yuen Long councilors to investigate MTR mob attack |url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=139622 |work=The Standard |date=7 January 2020}}</ref> The Hong Kong Police Force refused a formal invitation to attend the council meeting. Former student leader [[Tommy Cheung (student leader)|Tommy Cheung]], now district councillor for [[Yuen Lung (constituency)|Yuen Lung constituency]], was elected chairman of the task force.<ref name=\"scmpdistrictcouncil\">{{cite news |last1=Lam |first1=Jeffie |title=Hong Kong protests: district council sets up task force to investigate mob attack at Yuen Long MTR station |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3044996/hong-kong-protests-district-council-sets-task-force |work=South China Morning Post |date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B8QRzVbfLCQ|script-title=zh:\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c|trans-title=Dark Night of Yuen Long|series=\u7d93\u7def\u7dda [Now Report]|publisher=Now TV|location=Hong Kong|language=yue|date=28 July 2019|via=YouTube|type=Television production}}\n* {{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=16CiwPChpr0|script-title=zh:721\u5143\u6717\u9ed1\u591c|trans-title=721 Yuen Long Nightmare|series=\u93d7\u93d8\u96c6 [Hong Kong Connection]|publisher=RTHK|location=Hong Kong|language=Yue|date=29 July 2019|via=YouTube|type=Television production}}\n* {{cite video |url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000006624535/hong-kong-protest-police-triad-investigation.html |title=Visual Investigation: When a Mob Attacked Protesters in Hong Kong, the Police Walked Away |website=The New York Times |accessdate=30 July 2019 |type=Documentary}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019 Hong Kong protests}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yuen Long attack, 2019}}\n[[Category:2019 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2019]]\n[[Category:July 2019 events in China]]\n[[Category:July 2019 events of the 2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]]\n[[Category:Attacks on railway stations]]\n[[Category:Organized crime events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Organised crime in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Ninaschotport12", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unnecessarily over detailing to 1 victim of 45 victims including children , journalists , lawmakers , elderly and many.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Yuen_Long_attack"}
{"title_page": "Nazi concentration camp badge", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n[[File:Kennzeichen f\u00fcr Schutzh\u00e4ftlinge in den Konzentrationslagern.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Nazi camp ID-emblems in a 1936 German illustration]]\n'''Nazi concentration camp badges''', primarily triangles, were part of the system of [[identification in Nazi camps]]. They were used in the [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camps]] in the [[Nazism|Nazi]]-occupied countries to identify the reason the prisoners had been placed there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyplace.com/worldwar2/holocaust/h-dach-early.htm|title=The History Place - Holocaust Timeline: Nazis Open Dachau Concentration Camp|website=historyplace.com|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> The triangles were made of fabric and were sewn on jackets and trousers of the prisoners. These mandatory [[badge of shame|badges of shame]] had specific meanings indicated by their colour and shape. Such emblems helped guards assign tasks to the detainees. For example, a guard at a glance could see if someone were a convicted criminal (green patch) and thus likely of a tough temperament suitable for ''[[Kapo (concentration camp)|kapo]]'' duty.\n\nSomeone with an escape suspect mark usually would not be assigned to work squads operating outside the camp fence. Someone wearing an F could be called upon to help translate guards' spoken instructions to a trainload of new arrivals from France. Some historical monuments quote the badge-imagery, with the use of a triangle being a sort of visual shorthand to symbolize all camp victims.\n\nThe modern-day use of a [[pink triangle]] emblem to symbolize gay rights is a response to the camp identification patches.\n\n== Badge coding system ==\n[[File:Wikpedia system of identification German camps.png|thumb|right|Prisoners' distinguishing badges]]\nThe system of badges varied between the camps and in the later stages of [[World War II]] the use of badges dwindled in some camps and became increasingly accidental in others. The following description is based on the badge coding system used before and during the early stages of the war in the [[Dachau concentration camp]], which had one of the more elaborate coding systems.\n\nShape was chosen by analogy with the common [[Warning sign|triangular road hazard signs]] in Germany that denote warnings to motorists. Here, a triangle is called inverted because its base is up while one of its angles points down.\n\n=== Single triangles ===\n* Red triangle \u2013 [[political prisoner]]s: [[social democracy|social democrats]], [[Socialism|socialists]], [[communism|communists]] and [[anarchism|anarchists]]; [[Individuals and groups assisting Jews during the Holocaust|rescuers of Jews]]; trade unionists; and [[Suppression of Freemasonry|Freemasons]].\n* Green triangle \u2013 convicts and criminals (often working as ''[[Kapo (concentration camp)|kapos]]'').\n* Blue triangle \u2013 foreign forced laborers and [[emigrants]].\n* [[Purple triangle]] \u2013 primarily [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] (over 99%) as well as members of other small pacifist religious groups.<ref group=notes>Johannes S. Wrobel (June 2006). \"Jehovah's Witnesses in National Socialist Concentration Camps, 1933\u201345\". ''Religion, State & Society''. Vol. 34. No. 2. pp. 89\u2013125. \"The concentration camp prisoner category 'Bible Student' at times apparently included a few members from small Bible Student splinter groups, as well as adherents of other religious groups which played only a secondary role during the time of the National Socialist regime, such as Adventists, Baptists and the New Apostolic community (Garbe 1999, pp. 82, 406; Zeiger, 2001, p. 72). Since their numbers in the camps were quite small compared with the total number of Jehovah\u2019s Witness prisoners, I shall not consider them separately in this article. Historian Antje Zeiger (2001, p. 88) writes about Sachsenhausen camp: 'In May 1938, every tenth prisoner was a Jehovah's Witness. Less than one percent of the Witnesses included other religious nonconformists (Adventists, Baptists, pacifists), who were placed in the same prisoner classification.'\"</ref>\n* [[Pink triangle]] \u2013 primarily homosexual men and those identified as such (e.g., [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] men and [[Trans woman|trans women]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tgdor.org/holocaust.shtml|title=2008 Houston Transgender Day of Remembrance: Transgenders and Nazi Germany|author=Cristian Williams|website=tgdor.org|accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://arcspace.com/feature/canadian-national-holocaust-monument/|title=Canadian National Holocaust Monument / Studio Libeskind|website=arcspace.com|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/2012/11/illuminating-the-darkness/|title=Illuminating the Darkness|website=outsmartmagazine.com|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref> as well as sexual offenders including [[rapists]], [[pedophiles]] and [[bestiality|zoophiles]].<ref>Richard Plant (1988). ''The Pink Triangle: The Nazi War Against Homosexuals''. Owl Books. {{ISBN|0-8050-0600-1}}.</ref>\n* [[Black triangle (badge)|Black triangle]] \u2013 people who were deemed asocial elements (''asozial'') and work-shy (''arbeitsscheu''), including the following:\n** [[Romani people|Roma and Sinti]] (Gypsies). They wore the black triangle with a Z notation (for ''Zigeuner'', meaning Gypsy) to the right of the triangle's point.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/glossB.html|title=Glossary|website=jewishvirtuallibrary.org|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> Male Romani were later assigned a brown triangle. Female Romani were still deemed asocials as they were stereotyped as petty criminals (prostitutes, kidnappers and fortune tellers).\n** [[Mentally ill]] and [[mentally disabled]]. Their triangles were inscribed with the word ''Bl\u00f6d'', meaning stupid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holocaustrevealed.org/badges.htm|title=Badges|website=holocaustrevealed.org|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n** [[Alcoholism|Alcoholics]] and [[addiction|drug addicts]].\n** [[Homelessness|Vagrants]] and [[beggars]].\n** [[Pacifism|Pacifists]] and [[Conscientious objector|conscription resisters]].\n** Prostitutes.<ref>Claudia Schoppmann (1990). ''Nationalsozialistische Sexualpolitik und weibliche Homosexualit\u00e4t''. Dissertation, FU Berlin. Centaurus, Pfaffenweiler 1991 (revisited 2nd edition 1997). {{ISBN|3-89085-538-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2 February 2008|date=1 February 2001|url=http://www.oxfordstudent.com/ht2001wk3/Columns/black_triangle_women|title=Black triangle women|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212113936/http://www.oxfordstudent.com/ht2001wk3/Columns/black_triangle_women|archivedate=12 February 2009}}</ref>\n** Lesbians.<ref name=\"Elman\">{{cite journal|last1=Elman PhD|first1=R. Amy|title=Triangles and Tribulations: The Politics of Nazi Symbols|journal=[[Journal of Homosexuality]]|date=1996|volume=30|issue=3|pages=1\u201311|issn=0091-8369}}</ref> \n\n* Brown triangle \u2013 Romani males.\n* Uninverted red triangle \u2013 an enemy [[Prisoner of war|POW]] (''Sonderh\u00e4ftling'', meaning special detainee), a spy or traitor (''Aktionsh\u00e4ftling'', meaning activities detainee), or a military [[deserter]] or criminal (''Wehrmachtsangeh\u00f6riger'', meaning service member).\n\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some period examples of the single triangle design at Nazi camps\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-78612-0007, KZ Sachsenhausen, H\u00e4ftlinge bei Z\u00e4hlappel.jpg|Single-triangle badges in various colors visible on [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] detainees\nFile:Prisoners in the concentration camp at Sachsenhausen, Germany, December 19, 1938. Heinrich Hoffman Collection. - NARA - 540177.tif|Single-triangles visible on [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainees\nFile:Purple Triangle.JPG|Specimen indicating one of [[Jehovah's Witnesses]]\nFile:Prisoners' Uniforms with Red Triangles of Political Prisoners - Museum Exhibit - Dachau Concentration Camp Site - Dachau - Bavaria - Germany.jpg|Red emblems of a political enemy on a [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] detainee's clothing.{{note|Photo by Adam Jones.}}\nFile:Prisoners in the concentration camp at Sachsenhausen, Germany, 12-19-1938 - NARA - 540175.jpg|More [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainees\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 152-27-11A, Dachau, Konzentrationslager.jpg|[[Black triangle (badge)|Black triangles]] visible on the trousers of [[Romani people|Romani]] detainees at [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]]\nFile:Benedikt Kautsky.jpg|United States Army photo of [[Buchenwald]] survivor {{ill|Benedikt Kautsky|de}}\nFile:A sick Polish survivor in the Hannover-Ahlem concentration camp receives medicine from a German Red Cross worker.jpg|Liberated [[Neuengamme concentration camp|Neuengamme]] survivor standing on the right has a triangle patch with a top-bar\n</gallery>\n\n=== Double triangles ===\n{{see also|Yellow badge}}\nDouble-triangle badges resembled two superimposed triangles forming a [[Star of David]], a Jewish symbol.\n* Red inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing a Jewish political prisoner\n* Blue inverted triangle superimposed upon a red one representing foreign forced labour and political prisoner (for example, Spanish Republicans in Mauthausen)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entomelloso.com/de-tomelloso-a-mauthausen/|title=De Tomelloso a Mauthausen|website=entomelloso.com|date=12 January 2017|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n* Green inverted triangle upon a yellow one representing a Jewish habitual criminal\n* Purple inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing one of Jehovah's Witnesses of Jewish descent<ref>Note that since Jew was defined along racial lines, such as by the [[Racial policy of Nazi Germany#The Nuremberg Laws|Nuremberg Laws]], Jews could be classified as Jehovah's Witnesses.</ref>\n* Pink inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing a Jewish \"sexual offender\", typically a gay or bisexual man\n* Black inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing asocial and work-shy Jew\n* Voided black inverted triangle superimposed over a yellow triangle representing a Jew convicted of [[miscegenation]] and labelled as a ''Rassensch\u00e4nder'' (race defiler).\n* Yellow inverted triangle superimposed over a black triangle representing an [[Aryan]] (woman) convicted of miscegenation and labelled as a ''Rassensch\u00e4nder'' (race defiler).\nLike those who wore pink and green triangles, people in the bottom two categories would have been convicted in criminal courts.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some period examples of the double triangle design at Nazi camps\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:Prisoners in the concentration camp at Sachsenhausen, Germany, December 19, 1938. Heinrich Hoffman Collection. - NARA - 540178.tif|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainee with glasses in the foreground wears a two-color ID-emblem\nFile:Buchenwald Disabled Jews 13132 crop.jpg|Disabled Jews with a black triangle on a yellow triangle, meaning asocial Jews, [[Buchenwald]], 1938.\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 152-27-13A, Dachau Konzentrationslager, H\u00e4ftlinge beim Appell.jpg|Part of a [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] roll call\u2014badges visible on detainees\nFile:SarahEwart-066.jpg|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainee's red political enemy triangle atop a yellow Jew triangle (lower left)\n</gallery>\n\n=== Distinguishing marks ===\nIn addition to color-coding, non-German prisoners were marked by the first letter of the German name for their home country or ethnic group. Red triangle with a letter, for example: B (''Belgier'', [[Belgium|Belgians]]), E (''Engl\u00e4nder'', English), F (''Franzosen'', French), H (''Holl\u00e4nder'', [[Dutch people|Dutch]]), I (''Italiener'', Italians), J<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/vesti-dana/U-Aushvicu-na-vest-o-oslobodjenju-Beograda.sr.html|title=\u0423 \u0410\u0443\u0448\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0443, \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442 \u043e \u043e\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0452\u0435\u045a\u0443 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430|author=J. Beokovi\u0107|website=politika.rs|date=19 October 2009|language=Serbian|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> (''Jugoslawen'', [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslavs]]), N (''Norweger'', Norwegian), [[P (Nazi symbol)|P]] (''Polen'', [[Poles]]), S (''republikanische Spanier'', [[Second Spanish Republic|Republican Spanish]]) T (''Tscheche'', [[Czechs]]), U (''Ungarn'', [[Magyars|Hungarians]]), or a Z notation next to a black triangle (''Zigeuner'', [[Romani people|Gypsy]]).\n\nPolish emigrant laborers originally wore a purple diamond with a yellow backing. A letter P (for ''Polen'') was cut out of the purple cloth to show the yellow backing beneath.  \n\nFurthermore, repeat offenders (''r\u00fcckf\u00e4llige'', meaning recidivists) would receive bars over their stars or triangles, a different colour for a different crime.\n* A political prisoner would have a red bar over their star or triangle.\n* A professional criminal would have a green bar.\n* A foreign forced laborer would not have a blue bar (as their impressment was for the duration of the war), but might have a different coloured bar if they were drawn from another pool of inmates. \n* One of Jehovah's Witnesses would have a purple bar.\n* A homosexual or sex offender would have a pink bar.\n* An asocial would have a black bar.\n* Roma and Sinti (Gypsies) would usually be incarcerated in special sub-camps until they died and so would not normally receive a repeat stripe.\n\nLater in the war (late 1944), to save cloth Jewish prisoners wore a yellow bar over a regular point-down triangle to indicate their status. For instance, regular Jews would wear a yellow bar over a red triangle while Jewish criminals would wear a yellow bar over a green triangle.\n\n==== Special marks ====\n{{More citations needed|section|date=October 2019}}\nMany various markings and combinations existed. A prisoner would usually have at least two and possibly more than six.\n\nLimited preventative custody detainee (''Befristete Vorbeugungshaft H\u00e4ftling'', or BV) was the term for general criminals (who wore green triangles with no special marks). They originally were only supposed to be incarcerated at the camp until their term expired and then they would be released. However, when the war began they were confined indefinitely for its duration.\n\n''Erziehungsh\u00e4ftlinge'' (reformatory inmates) wore E or EH in large black letters on a white square. They were made up of intellectuals and respected community members who could organize and lead a resistance movement, suspicious persons picked up in sweeps or stopped at checkpoints, people caught performing conspiratorial activities or acts and inmates who broke work discipline. They were assigned to hard labor for 6 to 8 weeks and were then released. It was hoped that the threat of permanent incarceration at hard labor  would deter them from further mischief.\n\n''Polizeih\u00e4ftlinge'' (police inmates), short for ''Polizeilich Sicherungsverwahrte H\u00e4ftlinge'' (police secure custody inmates), wore either PH in large black letters on a white square or the letter S (for ''Sicherungsverwahrt'' \u2014 secure custody) on a green triangle. To save expense, some camps had them just wear their civilian clothes without markings. Records used the letter PSV (''Polizeilich Sicherungsverwahrt'') to designate them. They were people awaiting trial by a police court-martial or who were already convicted. They were detained in a special jail barracks until they were executed.\n\nSome camps assigned ''[[Nacht und Nebel]]'' (night and fog) prisoners had them wear two large letters NN in yellow.\n\nSoviet prisoners of war (''russische Kriegsgefangenen'') assigned to work camps (''Arbeitslager'') wore two large letters SU (for ''sowjetischer Untermensch'', meaning Soviet sub-human){{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} in yellow and had vertical stripes painted on their uniforms. They were the few who had not been shot out of hand or died of neglect from untreated wounds, exposure to the elements, or starvation before they could reach a camp. They performed hard labor. Some joined [[Andrey Vlasov|Andrey Vlasov's]] [[Russian Liberation Army|Liberation Army]] to fight for the Germans.\n\nLabor education detainees (''Arbeitserziehung H\u00e4ftling'') wore a white letter A on their black triangle. This stood for ''Arbeitsscheuer'' (work-shy person), designating as lazy social undesirables like Gypsies, petty criminals (e.g. prostitutes and pickpockets), alcoholics/drug addicts and vagrants. They were usually assigned to work at labor camps.\n\n''Asoziale'' (anti-socials) inmates wore a plain black triangle. They were considered either too \"selfish\" or \"deviant\" to contribute to society or were considered too impaired to support themselves. They were therefore considered a burden. This category included pacifists and conscription resisters, petty or habitual criminals, the mentally ill and the mentally and/or physically disabled. They were usually executed or euthanized.\n\nThe Wehrmacht ''[[Strafbattalion]]'' (punishment battalion) and SS ''Bew\u00e4hrungstruppe'' (probation company) were military punishment units. They consisted of [[Wehrmacht]] and SS military criminals, SS personnel convicted by an Honor Court of bad conduct and civilian criminals for which military service was either the assigned punishment or a voluntary replacement of imprisonment. They wore regular uniforms, but were forbidden rank or unit insignia until they had proven themselves in combat. They wore an uninverted (point-upwards) red triangle on their upper sleeves to indicate their status. Most were used for hard labor, \"special tasks\" (unwanted dangerous jobs like defusing landmines or running phone cables) or were used as [[forlorn hope]]s or [[cannon fodder]]. The infamous [[Dirlewanger Brigade]] was an example of a regular unit created from such personnel.\n\nA ''Strafkompanie'' (punishment company) was a hard labor unit in the camps. Inmates assigned to it wore a black roundel bordered white under their triangle patch.\n\nPrisoners \"suspected of [attempting to] escape\" (''Fluchtverd\u00e4chtiger'') wore a red roundel bordered white under their triangle patch. If also assigned to hard labor, they wore the red roundel under their black ''Strafkompanie'' roundel.\n\nA prisoner-functionary (''Funktionsh\u00e4ftling''), or ''[[Kapo (concentration camp)|kapo]]'' (boss), wore a cloth [[brassard]] (their ''Kennzeichen'', or identifying mark) to indicate their status. They served as camp guards (''Lagerpolizei''), barracks clerks (''Blockschreiber'') and the senior prisoners (''\u00e4ltesten'', meaning elders) at the camp (''lager\u00e4ltester''), barracks (''block\u00e4ltester'') and room (''stuben\u00e4ltester'') levels of camp organization. They received privileges like bigger and sometimes better food rations, better quarters (or even a private room), luxuries (like tobacco or alcohol) and access to the camp's facilities (like the showers or the pool). Failure to please their captors meant demotion and loss of privileges and an almost certain death at the hands of their fellow inmates.\n\nDetainees wearing civilian clothing (more common later in the war) instead of the striped uniforms were often marked with a prominent X on the back.<ref name=Saidel>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zglu2RvoLmgC&lpg=PA76&ots=ElAQpjF6Aw&dq=%22an%20x%22%20%22concentration%20camp%22%20-%22x-men%22%20-%22x-ray%22&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q=%22an%20x%22%20%22concentration%20camp%22%20-%22x-men%22%20-%22x-ray%22&f=false|title=The Jewish Women of Ravensbr\u00fcck Concentration Camp|author=Rochelle G. Saidel|year=2006|page=76|accessdate=20 May 2013}}</ref> This made for an ''[[ersatz]]'' prisoner uniform. For permanence, such Xs were made with white oil paint, with sewn-on cloth strips, or were cut (with underlying jacket-liner fabric providing the contrasting color). Detainees would be compelled to sew their number and (if applicable) a triangle emblem onto the fronts of such X-ed clothing.<ref name=Saidel/>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some period examples of nationality-letter marking at Nazi camps\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:13cwik.jpg|F on red triangle (French political enemy) on [[Buchenwald]] clothing of Dr. Joseph Brau{{note|Photo by Dominique Brau.}}\nFile:A1vestonf.JPG|F-triangle on [[Buchenwald]] clothing of Dr. Joseph Brau{{note|Photo by Dominique Brau.}}\nFile:Nazi_concentration_camp_uniform_fabric_sample.jpg|Specimen meaning Polish political enemy\nFile:Numer obozowy KL Stutthof 29659.JPG|[[Stutthof concentration camp|Stutthof]] detainee 29659 \u2013 Lidia G\u0142\u00f3wczewska, which showcase the letter P on a red triangle for Polish political enemy\nFile:IgnacyKwarta.png|[[Auschwitz]] detainee Ignacy Kwarta wears a red P-triangle, meaning a Polish political enemy\nFile:Buchenwald Prisoners 83718.jpg|Dutch Jews wearing a yellow star and the letter N for Niederl\u00e4nder at [[Buchenwald]]\nFile:SarahEwart-069.JPG|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]]-issued red F emblem for a French political enemy\nFile:Kazimierkiewicz georg 1 hpk.jpg|Emblems were also used on some detainee ID-cards as shown here on the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen]] card of Polish scientist [[Jerzy Ka\u017amirkiewicz]], where a P-triangle appears{{note|The card also has an ink stamp indicating Dehomag data-entry.}}\nFile:Toasting Polish Dachau.jpg|[[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] survivors toast their liberation as the man standing in center between the bottles wears a P triangle.\nFile:The Liberation of Bergen-belsen Concentration Camp, April 1945 BU4010.jpg|Liberated [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] survivor with a late war ''[[ersatz]]'' variant (left) showcasing no cloth patch, but a prominent N marked on the outer clothes\n</gallery>\n\n== Table of camp inmate markings ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=\"12%\"|\n!width=\"12%\"|''Politisch''<br>Political prisoner\n!width=\"12%\"|''Berufsverbrecher''<br>Professional criminal\n!width=\"12%\"|''Emigrant''<br>Foreign forced laborer\n!width=\"12%\"|''Bibelforscher''<br>Bible Student<br>([[Jehovah's Witnesses|Jehovah\u2019s Witness]])\n!width=\"12%\"|''Homosexuell''<br>Male homosexual/sex offender\n!width=\"12%\"|''Arbeitsscheu''/''Asozial''<br>Work-shy/[[Asociality|Asocial]]\n!width=\"12%\"|''Zigeuner''<br>Gypsy<br>(Roma or Sinti male)\n|-\n!Basic colours\n|[[File:Red triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle.svg|50px]]\n|-\n!Markings for repeaters\n|[[File:Red triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|-\n!Inmates of ''Strafkompanie'' (punishment companies)\n|[[File:Red triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|-\n!Markings for Jews\n|[[File:Red triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"3\"|Political prisoner nationality markings <br>The capital letter of the name of the country on a red triangle\n!Belgian (''Belgier'')\n!Czech (''Tscheche'')\n!French (''Franzose'')\n!Polish (''Pole'')\n!Spanish (''Spanier'')\n|-\n|[[File:Belgian political prisoner triangle (2).gif|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle Czech.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle French.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle Pole.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle Spainish.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Special markings\n!''J\u00fcdischer Rassensch\u00e4nder''<br>Jewish race defiler\n!''Rassensch\u00e4nderin''<br>Female race defiler\n!Escape suspect\n!''H\u00e4ftlingsnummer''<br>Inmate number\n!colspan=2|''Kennzeichen f\u00fcr Funktionsh\u00e4ftlinge''<br>Special inmates' brown armband\n!Enemy [[POW]] or [[deserter]]\n|-\n|[[File:Male race defiler.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Female race defiler2.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Escape suspect.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Inmate number.svg|100px]]\n|colspan=2|[[File:Special inmate.svg|100px]]\n|[[File:Armed forces red triangle.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n|-\n!Example\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Sleeve badges.svg|70px]]\n|colspan=\"6\"|Marks were worn in descending order as follows: inmate number, repeater bar, triangle or star, member of [[penal battalion]], escape suspect. In this example, the inmate is a Jewish convict with multiple convictions, serving in a ''[[Strafkompanie]]'' ([[penal battalion|penal unit]]) and who is suspected of trying to escape.\n|}\n\n== Postwar use ==\nTriangle-motifs appear on many postwar memorials to the victims of the Nazis. Most triangles are plain while some others bear [[Nazi concentration camp badges#Other badges|nationality-letters]]. The otherwise potentially puzzling designs are a direct reference to the identification patches used in the camps. On such monuments, typically an inverted (point down, base up) triangle (especially if red) evokes all victims, including also the [[Holocaust#Non-Jewish|non-Jewish victims]] like Slavs, Poles, communists, homosexuals, [[Romani people|Roma and Sinti]] (see [[Porajmos]]), the handicapped (see [[Action T4]]) Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses, and [[Nazi crimes against Soviet POWs|Soviet POWs]].  An inverted triangle colored pink would symbolize gay male victims.  A non-inverted (base down, point up) triangle and/or a yellow triangle is generally more evocative of the Jewish victims.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some examples of camp triangle emblems on monuments and related uses\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:KZ Sachsenhausen - zentrales Mahnmal.JPG|At [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]]\nFile:Todesmarsch Gedenkstein Breitenfeld.JPG|A [[Mittelbau-Dora|Dora]] ''Todesmarsch'' [[Death marches (Holocaust)|(death march)]] roadside tablet marked only with the date and a red triangle\nFile:Holocaust Memorial in Estonia.jpg|On the [[Klooga concentration camp|Klooga]] Jewish victims' memorial\nFile:Crawinkel Gedenktafel.JPG|On a [[Buchenwald]] ''Todesmarsch'' [[Death marches (Holocaust)|(death march)]] route historical marker\nFile:Death March Memorial Plaque, Oranienburg.jpg|On a [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] death march route [[historical marker]]\nFile:Belower-Damm-Wittstock-Dosse-Mahnmal.jpg|Monument (in the village of [[Grabow-Below]]) for [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]] death march victims\nFile:Denkmal KZ Woebbelin4.jpg|On a [[W\u00f6bbelin concentration camp|W\u00f6bbelin]] memorial stone\nFile:Gedenkst\u00e4tte_Lindenring_(2).jpg|Boulder (in Lindenring) for 2,000 women victims of [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]]\nFile:Cenoteph of Cap Arcona.JPG|On a ''[[SS Cap Arcona (1927)|Cap Arcona]]'' incident memorial\nFile:Neustadt-Glewe VVN-Denkmal 2008-01-03.jpg|At the [[Neustadt-Glewe]] concentration camp memorial\nFile:French monument Mauthausen 1243.JPG|F-triangle at [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen-Gusen]] honors French victims\nFile:Croix du Prisonnier Politique 1940-1945.jpg|B-triangle incorporated into the Belgian [[Political Prisoner's Cross 1940\u20131945|Political Prisoner's Cross]]\nFile:KZ-Hinzert-Plakette-Nacht-und-Nebel.jpg|F-triangle at [[Hinzert concentration camp|Hinzert]] honors French victims, especially of the ''[[Nacht und Nebel]]'' program\nFile:Stamps of Germany (DDR) 1973, MiNr 1878.jpg|On a [[Langenstein-Zwieberge]] memorial (pictured on an East German stamp).\nFile:Han Seelhorst Mahnmal KZ Opfer 01.PNG|On a monument to [[Neuengamme concentration camp|Neuengamme]] victims in [[Hamburg]], where the letters KZ are not nationality-letters, but rather are the German abbreviation for ''Konzentrationslager''<br>(concentration camp)\nFile:Ludwigsfelde Friedhof Gedenkstein Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer.JPG|On a memorial to victims killed at Genshagen (right panel), where the letters KZ are not nationality-letters but rather are the German abbreviation for ''Konzentrationslager''<br>(concentration camp)\nFile:Denkmal f\u00fcr die Opfer der NS-Konzentrationslager Zgorzelec.JPG|P-triangle at a Zgorzelec memorial\nFile:Krzy\u017c O\u015bwi\u0119cimski-awers.jpg|P-triangle on the [[Auschwitz Cross|Polish medal for camp victims]]\nFile:Memorial with Prisoners Triangle Badges and Star of David Badge - Dachau Concentration Camp Site - Dachau - Bavaria - Germany.jpg|Various badges on a [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] memorial{{note|Photo by Adam Jones.}}\nFile:In memory of homosexual.JPG|[[Pink triangle]] (''Rosa Winkel'' in German) memorial for gay men killed at [[Buchenwald]]\nFile:Gedenktafel Rosa Winkel Nollendorfplatz.jpg|In the Berlin [[Nollendorfplatz (Berlin U-Bahn)|Nollendorfplatz subway station]], a pink triangle plaque honors gay male victims{{note|Photo by Manfred Brueckels.}}\nFile:Ac.homomonument.jpg|Amsterdam's ''[[Homomonument]]'' uses pink triangles symbolically to memorialize gay men killed in the [[Holocaust]] and also victims of [[Gay bashing|anti-gay violence generally]]\nFile:Pink triangle on Twin Peaks (19055079410).jpg|Every year, a pink triangle is erected on [[Twin Peaks (San Francisco)|Twin Peaks]] in San Francisco during [[San Francisco Pride|Pride weekend]].\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* Richard Plant (1988). ''The Pink Triangle: The Nazi War Against Homosexuals''. Owl Books. {{ISBN|0-8050-0600-1}}.\n* [http://www.historyplace.com/worldwar2/holocaust/h-dach-early.htm Camp badge chart at historyplace.com].\n* [http://www.friends-partners.org/partners/beyond-the-pale/eng_captions/54-5.html Additional camp badge chart].\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|Nazi concentration camp badges}}\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/index.php?ModuleId=10005378&Type=normal+article United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]. Classification system in Nazi concentration camps.\n* [https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/markings.html Stars, triangles and markings]. Jewish Virtual Library.\n* [https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/gaycomp.html Gay Prisoners in Concentration Camps as Compared with Jehovah's Witnesses and Political Prisoners]. Ruediger Lautmann.\n\n{{The Holocaust}}{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Terminology of Nazi concentration camps]]\n[[Category:Identity documents of Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:The Holocaust]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n[[File:Kennzeichen f\u00fcr Schutzh\u00e4ftlinge in den Konzentrationslagern.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Nazi camp ID-emblems in a 1936 German illustration]]\n'''Nazi concentration camp badges''', primarily triangles, were part of the system of [[identification in Nazi camps]]. They were used in the [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camps]] in the [[Nazism|Nazi]]-occupied countries to identify the reason the prisoners had been placed there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyplace.com/worldwar2/holocaust/h-dach-early.htm|title=The History Place - Holocaust Timeline: Nazis Open Dachau Concentration Camp|website=historyplace.com|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> The triangles were made of fabric and were sewn on jackets and trousers of the prisoners. These mandatory [[badge of shame|badges of shame]] had specific meanings indicated by their colour and shape. Such emblems helped guards assign tasks to the detainees. For example, a guard at a glance could see if someone were a convicted criminal (green patch) and thus likely of a tough temperament suitable for ''[[Kapo (concentration camp)|kapo]]'' duty.\n\nSomeone with an escape suspect mark usually would not be assigned to work squads operating outside the camp fence. Someone wearing an F could be called upon to help translate guards' spoken instructions to a trainload of new arrivals from France. Some historical monuments quote the badge-imagery, with the use of a triangle being a sort of visual shorthand to symbolize all camp victims.\n\nThe modern-day use of a [[pink triangle]] emblem to symbolize gay rights is a response to the camp identification patches.\n\n== Badge coding system ==\nThe system of badges varied between the camps and in the later stages of [[World War II]] the use of badges dwindled in some camps and became increasingly accidental in others. The following description is based on the badge coding system used before and during the early stages of the war in the [[Dachau concentration camp]], which had one of the more elaborate coding systems.\n\nShape was chosen by analogy with the common [[Warning sign|triangular road hazard signs]] in Germany that denote warnings to motorists. Here, a triangle is called inverted because its base is up while one of its angles points down.\n\n=== Single triangles ===\n* Red triangle \u2013 [[political prisoner]]s: [[social democracy|social democrats]], [[Socialism|socialists]], [[communism|communists]] and [[anarchism|anarchists]]; [[Individuals and groups assisting Jews during the Holocaust|rescuers of Jews]]; trade unionists; and [[Suppression of Freemasonry|Freemasons]].\n* Green triangle \u2013 convicts and criminals (often working as ''[[Kapo (concentration camp)|kapos]]'').\n* Blue triangle \u2013 foreign forced laborers and [[emigrants]].\n* [[Purple triangle]] \u2013 primarily [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] (over 99%) as well as members of other small pacifist religious groups.<ref group=notes>Johannes S. Wrobel (June 2006). \"Jehovah's Witnesses in National Socialist Concentration Camps, 1933\u201345\". ''Religion, State & Society''. Vol. 34. No. 2. pp. 89\u2013125. \"The concentration camp prisoner category 'Bible Student' at times apparently included a few members from small Bible Student splinter groups, as well as adherents of other religious groups which played only a secondary role during the time of the National Socialist regime, such as Adventists, Baptists and the New Apostolic community (Garbe 1999, pp. 82, 406; Zeiger, 2001, p. 72). Since their numbers in the camps were quite small compared with the total number of Jehovah\u2019s Witness prisoners, I shall not consider them separately in this article. Historian Antje Zeiger (2001, p. 88) writes about Sachsenhausen camp: 'In May 1938, every tenth prisoner was a Jehovah's Witness. Less than one percent of the Witnesses included other religious nonconformists (Adventists, Baptists, pacifists), who were placed in the same prisoner classification.'\"</ref>\n* [[Pink triangle]] \u2013 primarily homosexual men and those identified as such (e.g., [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] men and [[Trans woman|trans women]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tgdor.org/holocaust.shtml|title=2008 Houston Transgender Day of Remembrance: Transgenders and Nazi Germany|author=Cristian Williams|website=tgdor.org|accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://arcspace.com/feature/canadian-national-holocaust-monument/|title=Canadian National Holocaust Monument / Studio Libeskind|website=arcspace.com|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outsmartmagazine.com/2012/11/illuminating-the-darkness/|title=Illuminating the Darkness|website=outsmartmagazine.com|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref> as well as sexual offenders including [[rapists]], [[pedophiles]] and [[bestiality|zoophiles]].<ref>Richard Plant (1988). ''The Pink Triangle: The Nazi War Against Homosexuals''. Owl Books. {{ISBN|0-8050-0600-1}}.</ref>\n* [[Black triangle (badge)|Black triangle]] \u2013 people who were deemed asocial elements (''asozial'') and work-shy (''arbeitsscheu''), including the following:\n** [[Romani people|Roma and Sinti]] (Gypsies). They wore the black triangle with a Z notation (for ''Zigeuner'', meaning Gypsy) to the right of the triangle's point.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/glossB.html|title=Glossary|website=jewishvirtuallibrary.org|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> Male Romani were later assigned a brown triangle. Female Romani were still deemed asocials as they were stereotyped as petty criminals (prostitutes, kidnappers and fortune tellers).\n** [[Mentally ill]] and [[mentally disabled]]. Their triangles were inscribed with the word ''Bl\u00f6d'', meaning stupid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holocaustrevealed.org/badges.htm|title=Badges|website=holocaustrevealed.org|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n** [[Alcoholism|Alcoholics]] and [[addiction|drug addicts]].\n** [[Homelessness|Vagrants]] and [[beggars]].\n** [[Pacifism|Pacifists]] and [[Conscientious objector|conscription resisters]].\n** Prostitutes.<ref>Claudia Schoppmann (1990). ''Nationalsozialistische Sexualpolitik und weibliche Homosexualit\u00e4t''. Dissertation, FU Berlin. Centaurus, Pfaffenweiler 1991 (revisited 2nd edition 1997). {{ISBN|3-89085-538-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2 February 2008|date=1 February 2001|url=http://www.oxfordstudent.com/ht2001wk3/Columns/black_triangle_women|title=Black triangle women|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212113936/http://www.oxfordstudent.com/ht2001wk3/Columns/black_triangle_women|archivedate=12 February 2009}}</ref>\n** Lesbians.<ref name=\"Elman\">{{cite journal|last1=Elman PhD|first1=R. Amy|title=Triangles and Tribulations: The Politics of Nazi Symbols|journal=[[Journal of Homosexuality]]|date=1996|volume=30|issue=3|pages=1\u201311|issn=0091-8369}}</ref> \n\n* Brown triangle \u2013 Romani males.\n* Uninverted red triangle \u2013 an enemy [[Prisoner of war|POW]] (''Sonderh\u00e4ftling'', meaning special detainee), a spy or traitor (''Aktionsh\u00e4ftling'', meaning activities detainee), or a military [[deserter]] or criminal (''Wehrmachtsangeh\u00f6riger'', meaning service member).\n\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some period examples of the single triangle design at Nazi camps\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-78612-0007, KZ Sachsenhausen, H\u00e4ftlinge bei Z\u00e4hlappel.jpg|Single-triangle badges in various colors visible on [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] detainees\nFile:Prisoners in the concentration camp at Sachsenhausen, Germany, December 19, 1938. Heinrich Hoffman Collection. - NARA - 540177.tif|Single-triangles visible on [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainees\nFile:Purple Triangle.JPG|Specimen indicating one of [[Jehovah's Witnesses]]\nFile:Prisoners' Uniforms with Red Triangles of Political Prisoners - Museum Exhibit - Dachau Concentration Camp Site - Dachau - Bavaria - Germany.jpg|Red emblems of a political enemy on a [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] detainee's clothing.{{note|Photo by Adam Jones.}}\nFile:Prisoners in the concentration camp at Sachsenhausen, Germany, 12-19-1938 - NARA - 540175.jpg|More [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainees\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 152-27-11A, Dachau, Konzentrationslager.jpg|[[Black triangle (badge)|Black triangles]] visible on the trousers of [[Romani people|Romani]] detainees at [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]]\nFile:Benedikt Kautsky.jpg|United States Army photo of [[Buchenwald]] survivor {{ill|Benedikt Kautsky|de}}\nFile:A sick Polish survivor in the Hannover-Ahlem concentration camp receives medicine from a German Red Cross worker.jpg|Liberated [[Neuengamme concentration camp|Neuengamme]] survivor standing on the right has a triangle patch with a top-bar\n</gallery>\n\n=== Double triangles ===\n{{see also|Yellow badge}}\nDouble-triangle badges resembled two superimposed triangles forming a [[Star of David]], a Jewish symbol.\n* Red inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing a Jewish political prisoner\n* Blue inverted triangle superimposed upon a red one representing foreign forced labour and political prisoner (for example, Spanish Republicans in Mauthausen)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entomelloso.com/de-tomelloso-a-mauthausen/|title=De Tomelloso a Mauthausen|website=entomelloso.com|date=12 January 2017|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n* Green inverted triangle upon a yellow one representing a Jewish habitual criminal\n* Purple inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing one of Jehovah's Witnesses of Jewish descent<ref>Note that since Jew was defined along racial lines, such as by the [[Racial policy of Nazi Germany#The Nuremberg Laws|Nuremberg Laws]], Jews could be classified as Jehovah's Witnesses.</ref>\n* Pink inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing a Jewish \"sexual offender\", typically a gay or bisexual man\n* Black inverted triangle superimposed upon a yellow one representing asocial and work-shy Jew\n* Voided black inverted triangle superimposed over a yellow triangle representing a Jew convicted of [[miscegenation]] and labelled as a ''Rassensch\u00e4nder'' (race defiler).\n* Yellow inverted triangle superimposed over a black triangle representing an [[Aryan]] (woman) convicted of miscegenation and labelled as a ''Rassensch\u00e4nder'' (race defiler).\nLike those who wore pink and green triangles, people in the bottom two categories would have been convicted in criminal courts.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some period examples of the double triangle design at Nazi camps\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:Prisoners in the concentration camp at Sachsenhausen, Germany, December 19, 1938. Heinrich Hoffman Collection. - NARA - 540178.tif|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainee with glasses in the foreground wears a two-color ID-emblem\nFile:Buchenwald Disabled Jews 13132 crop.jpg|Disabled Jews with a black triangle on a yellow triangle, meaning asocial Jews, [[Buchenwald]], 1938.\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 152-27-13A, Dachau Konzentrationslager, H\u00e4ftlinge beim Appell.jpg|Part of a [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] roll call\u2014badges visible on detainees\nFile:SarahEwart-066.jpg|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] detainee's red political enemy triangle atop a yellow Jew triangle (lower left)\n</gallery>\n\n=== Distinguishing marks ===\nIn addition to color-coding, non-German prisoners were marked by the first letter of the German name for their home country or ethnic group. Red triangle with a letter, for example: B (''Belgier'', [[Belgium|Belgians]]), E (''Engl\u00e4nder'', English), F (''Franzosen'', French), H (''Holl\u00e4nder'', [[Dutch people|Dutch]]), I (''Italiener'', Italians), J<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/vesti-dana/U-Aushvicu-na-vest-o-oslobodjenju-Beograda.sr.html|title=\u0423 \u0410\u0443\u0448\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0443, \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442 \u043e \u043e\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0452\u0435\u045a\u0443 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430|author=J. Beokovi\u0107|website=politika.rs|date=19 October 2009|language=Serbian|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> (''Jugoslawen'', [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslavs]]), N (''Norweger'', Norwegian), [[P (Nazi symbol)|P]] (''Polen'', [[Poles]]), S (''republikanische Spanier'', [[Second Spanish Republic|Republican Spanish]]) T (''Tscheche'', [[Czechs]]), U (''Ungarn'', [[Magyars|Hungarians]]), or a Z notation next to a black triangle (''Zigeuner'', [[Romani people|Gypsy]]).\n\nPolish emigrant laborers originally wore a purple diamond with a yellow backing. A letter P (for ''Polen'') was cut out of the purple cloth to show the yellow backing beneath.  \n\nFurthermore, repeat offenders (''r\u00fcckf\u00e4llige'', meaning recidivists) would receive bars over their stars or triangles, a different colour for a different crime.\n* A political prisoner would have a red bar over their star or triangle.\n* A professional criminal would have a green bar.\n* A foreign forced laborer would not have a blue bar (as their impressment was for the duration of the war), but might have a different coloured bar if they were drawn from another pool of inmates. \n* One of Jehovah's Witnesses would have a purple bar.\n* A homosexual or sex offender would have a pink bar.\n* An asocial would have a black bar.\n* Roma and Sinti (Gypsies) would usually be incarcerated in special sub-camps until they died and so would not normally receive a repeat stripe.\n\nLater in the war (late 1944), to save cloth Jewish prisoners wore a yellow bar over a regular point-down triangle to indicate their status. For instance, regular Jews would wear a yellow bar over a red triangle while Jewish criminals would wear a yellow bar over a green triangle.\n\n==== Special marks ====\n{{More citations needed|section|date=October 2019}}\nMany various markings and combinations existed. A prisoner would usually have at least two and possibly more than six.\n\nLimited preventative custody detainee (''Befristete Vorbeugungshaft H\u00e4ftling'', or BV) was the term for general criminals (who wore green triangles with no special marks). They originally were only supposed to be incarcerated at the camp until their term expired and then they would be released. However, when the war began they were confined indefinitely for its duration.\n\n''Erziehungsh\u00e4ftlinge'' (reformatory inmates) wore E or EH in large black letters on a white square. They were made up of intellectuals and respected community members who could organize and lead a resistance movement, suspicious persons picked up in sweeps or stopped at checkpoints, people caught performing conspiratorial activities or acts and inmates who broke work discipline. They were assigned to hard labor for 6 to 8 weeks and were then released. It was hoped that the threat of permanent incarceration at hard labor  would deter them from further mischief.\n\n''Polizeih\u00e4ftlinge'' (police inmates), short for ''Polizeilich Sicherungsverwahrte H\u00e4ftlinge'' (police secure custody inmates), wore either PH in large black letters on a white square or the letter S (for ''Sicherungsverwahrt'' \u2014 secure custody) on a green triangle. To save expense, some camps had them just wear their civilian clothes without markings. Records used the letter PSV (''Polizeilich Sicherungsverwahrt'') to designate them. They were people awaiting trial by a police court-martial or who were already convicted. They were detained in a special jail barracks until they were executed.\n\nSome camps assigned ''[[Nacht und Nebel]]'' (night and fog) prisoners had them wear two large letters NN in yellow.\n\nSoviet prisoners of war (''russische Kriegsgefangenen'') assigned to work camps (''Arbeitslager'') wore two large letters SU (for ''sowjetischer Untermensch'', meaning Soviet sub-human){{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} in yellow and had vertical stripes painted on their uniforms. They were the few who had not been shot out of hand or died of neglect from untreated wounds, exposure to the elements, or starvation before they could reach a camp. They performed hard labor. Some joined [[Andrey Vlasov|Andrey Vlasov's]] [[Russian Liberation Army|Liberation Army]] to fight for the Germans.\n\nLabor education detainees (''Arbeitserziehung H\u00e4ftling'') wore a white letter A on their black triangle. This stood for ''Arbeitsscheuer'' (work-shy person), designating as lazy social undesirables like Gypsies, petty criminals (e.g. prostitutes and pickpockets), alcoholics/drug addicts and vagrants. They were usually assigned to work at labor camps.\n\n''Asoziale'' (anti-socials) inmates wore a plain black triangle. They were considered either too \"selfish\" or \"deviant\" to contribute to society or were considered too impaired to support themselves. They were therefore considered a burden. This category included pacifists and conscription resisters, petty or habitual criminals, the mentally ill and the mentally and/or physically disabled. They were usually executed or euthanized.\n\nThe Wehrmacht ''[[Strafbattalion]]'' (punishment battalion) and SS ''Bew\u00e4hrungstruppe'' (probation company) were military punishment units. They consisted of [[Wehrmacht]] and SS military criminals, SS personnel convicted by an Honor Court of bad conduct and civilian criminals for which military service was either the assigned punishment or a voluntary replacement of imprisonment. They wore regular uniforms, but were forbidden rank or unit insignia until they had proven themselves in combat. They wore an uninverted (point-upwards) red triangle on their upper sleeves to indicate their status. Most were used for hard labor, \"special tasks\" (unwanted dangerous jobs like defusing landmines or running phone cables) or were used as [[forlorn hope]]s or [[cannon fodder]]. The infamous [[Dirlewanger Brigade]] was an example of a regular unit created from such personnel.\n\nA ''Strafkompanie'' (punishment company) was a hard labor unit in the camps. Inmates assigned to it wore a black roundel bordered white under their triangle patch.\n\nPrisoners \"suspected of [attempting to] escape\" (''Fluchtverd\u00e4chtiger'') wore a red roundel bordered white under their triangle patch. If also assigned to hard labor, they wore the red roundel under their black ''Strafkompanie'' roundel.\n\nA prisoner-functionary (''Funktionsh\u00e4ftling''), or ''[[Kapo (concentration camp)|kapo]]'' (boss), wore a cloth [[brassard]] (their ''Kennzeichen'', or identifying mark) to indicate their status. They served as camp guards (''Lagerpolizei''), barracks clerks (''Blockschreiber'') and the senior prisoners (''\u00e4ltesten'', meaning elders) at the camp (''lager\u00e4ltester''), barracks (''block\u00e4ltester'') and room (''stuben\u00e4ltester'') levels of camp organization. They received privileges like bigger and sometimes better food rations, better quarters (or even a private room), luxuries (like tobacco or alcohol) and access to the camp's facilities (like the showers or the pool). Failure to please their captors meant demotion and loss of privileges and an almost certain death at the hands of their fellow inmates.\n\nDetainees wearing civilian clothing (more common later in the war) instead of the striped uniforms were often marked with a prominent X on the back.<ref name=Saidel>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zglu2RvoLmgC&lpg=PA76&ots=ElAQpjF6Aw&dq=%22an%20x%22%20%22concentration%20camp%22%20-%22x-men%22%20-%22x-ray%22&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q=%22an%20x%22%20%22concentration%20camp%22%20-%22x-men%22%20-%22x-ray%22&f=false|title=The Jewish Women of Ravensbr\u00fcck Concentration Camp|author=Rochelle G. Saidel|year=2006|page=76|accessdate=20 May 2013}}</ref> This made for an ''[[ersatz]]'' prisoner uniform. For permanence, such Xs were made with white oil paint, with sewn-on cloth strips, or were cut (with underlying jacket-liner fabric providing the contrasting color). Detainees would be compelled to sew their number and (if applicable) a triangle emblem onto the fronts of such X-ed clothing.<ref name=Saidel/>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some period examples of nationality-letter marking at Nazi camps\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:13cwik.jpg|F on red triangle (French political enemy) on [[Buchenwald]] clothing of Dr. Joseph Brau{{note|Photo by Dominique Brau.}}\nFile:A1vestonf.JPG|F-triangle on [[Buchenwald]] clothing of Dr. Joseph Brau{{note|Photo by Dominique Brau.}}\nFile:Nazi_concentration_camp_uniform_fabric_sample.jpg|Specimen meaning Polish political enemy\nFile:Numer obozowy KL Stutthof 29659.JPG|[[Stutthof concentration camp|Stutthof]] detainee 29659 \u2013 Lidia G\u0142\u00f3wczewska, which showcase the letter P on a red triangle for Polish political enemy\nFile:IgnacyKwarta.png|[[Auschwitz]] detainee Ignacy Kwarta wears a red P-triangle, meaning a Polish political enemy\nFile:Buchenwald Prisoners 83718.jpg|Dutch Jews wearing a yellow star and the letter N for Niederl\u00e4nder at [[Buchenwald]]\nFile:SarahEwart-069.JPG|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]]-issued red F emblem for a French political enemy\nFile:Kazimierkiewicz georg 1 hpk.jpg|Emblems were also used on some detainee ID-cards as shown here on the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen]] card of Polish scientist [[Jerzy Ka\u017amirkiewicz]], where a P-triangle appears{{note|The card also has an ink stamp indicating Dehomag data-entry.}}\nFile:Toasting Polish Dachau.jpg|[[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] survivors toast their liberation as the man standing in center between the bottles wears a P triangle.\nFile:The Liberation of Bergen-belsen Concentration Camp, April 1945 BU4010.jpg|Liberated [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] survivor with a late war ''[[ersatz]]'' variant (left) showcasing no cloth patch, but a prominent N marked on the outer clothes\n</gallery>\n\n== Table of camp inmate markings ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=\"12%\"|\n!width=\"12%\"|''Politisch''<br>Political prisoner\n!width=\"12%\"|''Berufsverbrecher''<br>Professional criminal\n!width=\"12%\"|''Emigrant''<br>Foreign forced laborer\n!width=\"12%\"|''Bibelforscher''<br>Bible Student<br>([[Jehovah's Witnesses|Jehovah\u2019s Witness]])\n!width=\"12%\"|''Homosexuell''<br>Male homosexual/sex offender\n!width=\"12%\"|''Arbeitsscheu''/''Asozial''<br>Work-shy/[[Asociality|Asocial]]\n!width=\"12%\"|''Zigeuner''<br>Gypsy<br>(Roma or Sinti male)\n|-\n!Basic colours\n|[[File:Red triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle.svg|50px]]\n|-\n!Markings for repeaters\n|[[File:Red triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle repeater.svg|50px]]\n|-\n!Inmates of ''Strafkompanie'' (punishment companies)\n|[[File:Red triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle penal.svg|50px]]\n|-\n!Markings for Jews\n|[[File:Red triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Green triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Blue triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Purple triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Pink triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Black triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Brown triangle jew.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"3\"|Political prisoner nationality markings <br>The capital letter of the name of the country on a red triangle\n!Belgian (''Belgier'')\n!Czech (''Tscheche'')\n!French (''Franzose'')\n!Polish (''Pole'')\n!Spanish (''Spanier'')\n|-\n|[[File:Belgian political prisoner triangle (2).gif|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle Czech.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle French.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle Pole.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Red triangle Spainish.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Special markings\n!''J\u00fcdischer Rassensch\u00e4nder''<br>Jewish race defiler\n!''Rassensch\u00e4nderin''<br>Female race defiler\n!Escape suspect\n!''H\u00e4ftlingsnummer''<br>Inmate number\n!colspan=2|''Kennzeichen f\u00fcr Funktionsh\u00e4ftlinge''<br>Special inmates' brown armband\n!Enemy [[POW]] or [[deserter]]\n|-\n|[[File:Male race defiler.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Female race defiler2.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Escape suspect.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Inmate number.svg|100px]]\n|colspan=2|[[File:Special inmate.svg|100px]]\n|[[File:Armed forces red triangle.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"|\n|-\n!Example\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Sleeve badges.svg|70px]]\n|colspan=\"6\"|Marks were worn in descending order as follows: inmate number, repeater bar, triangle or star, member of [[penal battalion]], escape suspect. In this example, the inmate is a Jewish convict with multiple convictions, serving in a ''[[Strafkompanie]]'' ([[penal battalion|penal unit]]) and who is suspected of trying to escape.\n|}\n\n== Postwar use ==\nTriangle-motifs appear on many postwar memorials to the victims of the Nazis. Most triangles are plain while some others bear [[Nazi concentration camp badges#Other badges|nationality-letters]]. The otherwise potentially puzzling designs are a direct reference to the identification patches used in the camps. On such monuments, typically an inverted (point down, base up) triangle (especially if red) evokes all victims, including also the [[Holocaust#Non-Jewish|non-Jewish victims]] like Slavs, Poles, communists, homosexuals, [[Romani people|Roma and Sinti]] (see [[Porajmos]]), the handicapped (see [[Action T4]]) Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses, and [[Nazi crimes against Soviet POWs|Soviet POWs]].  An inverted triangle colored pink would symbolize gay male victims.  A non-inverted (base down, point up) triangle and/or a yellow triangle is generally more evocative of the Jewish victims.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Some examples of camp triangle emblems on monuments and related uses\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:KZ Sachsenhausen - zentrales Mahnmal.JPG|At [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]]\nFile:Todesmarsch Gedenkstein Breitenfeld.JPG|A [[Mittelbau-Dora|Dora]] ''Todesmarsch'' [[Death marches (Holocaust)|(death march)]] roadside tablet marked only with the date and a red triangle\nFile:Holocaust Memorial in Estonia.jpg|On the [[Klooga concentration camp|Klooga]] Jewish victims' memorial\nFile:Crawinkel Gedenktafel.JPG|On a [[Buchenwald]] ''Todesmarsch'' [[Death marches (Holocaust)|(death march)]] route historical marker\nFile:Death March Memorial Plaque, Oranienburg.jpg|On a [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]] death march route [[historical marker]]\nFile:Belower-Damm-Wittstock-Dosse-Mahnmal.jpg|Monument (in the village of [[Grabow-Below]]) for [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]] death march victims\nFile:Denkmal KZ Woebbelin4.jpg|On a [[W\u00f6bbelin concentration camp|W\u00f6bbelin]] memorial stone\nFile:Gedenkst\u00e4tte_Lindenring_(2).jpg|Boulder (in Lindenring) for 2,000 women victims of [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]]\nFile:Cenoteph of Cap Arcona.JPG|On a ''[[SS Cap Arcona (1927)|Cap Arcona]]'' incident memorial\nFile:Neustadt-Glewe VVN-Denkmal 2008-01-03.jpg|At the [[Neustadt-Glewe]] concentration camp memorial\nFile:French monument Mauthausen 1243.JPG|F-triangle at [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen-Gusen]] honors French victims\nFile:Croix du Prisonnier Politique 1940-1945.jpg|B-triangle incorporated into the Belgian [[Political Prisoner's Cross 1940\u20131945|Political Prisoner's Cross]]\nFile:KZ-Hinzert-Plakette-Nacht-und-Nebel.jpg|F-triangle at [[Hinzert concentration camp|Hinzert]] honors French victims, especially of the ''[[Nacht und Nebel]]'' program\nFile:Stamps of Germany (DDR) 1973, MiNr 1878.jpg|On a [[Langenstein-Zwieberge]] memorial (pictured on an East German stamp).\nFile:Han Seelhorst Mahnmal KZ Opfer 01.PNG|On a monument to [[Neuengamme concentration camp|Neuengamme]] victims in [[Hamburg]], where the letters KZ are not nationality-letters, but rather are the German abbreviation for ''Konzentrationslager''<br>(concentration camp)\nFile:Ludwigsfelde Friedhof Gedenkstein Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer.JPG|On a memorial to victims killed at Genshagen (right panel), where the letters KZ are not nationality-letters but rather are the German abbreviation for ''Konzentrationslager''<br>(concentration camp)\nFile:Denkmal f\u00fcr die Opfer der NS-Konzentrationslager Zgorzelec.JPG|P-triangle at a Zgorzelec memorial\nFile:Krzy\u017c O\u015bwi\u0119cimski-awers.jpg|P-triangle on the [[Auschwitz Cross|Polish medal for camp victims]]\nFile:Memorial with Prisoners Triangle Badges and Star of David Badge - Dachau Concentration Camp Site - Dachau - Bavaria - Germany.jpg|Various badges on a [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] memorial{{note|Photo by Adam Jones.}}\nFile:In memory of homosexual.JPG|[[Pink triangle]] (''Rosa Winkel'' in German) memorial for gay men killed at [[Buchenwald]]\nFile:Gedenktafel Rosa Winkel Nollendorfplatz.jpg|In the Berlin [[Nollendorfplatz (Berlin U-Bahn)|Nollendorfplatz subway station]], a pink triangle plaque honors gay male victims{{note|Photo by Manfred Brueckels.}}\nFile:Ac.homomonument.jpg|Amsterdam's ''[[Homomonument]]'' uses pink triangles symbolically to memorialize gay men killed in the [[Holocaust]] and also victims of [[Gay bashing|anti-gay violence generally]]\nFile:Pink triangle on Twin Peaks (19055079410).jpg|Every year, a pink triangle is erected on [[Twin Peaks (San Francisco)|Twin Peaks]] in San Francisco during [[San Francisco Pride|Pride weekend]].\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* Richard Plant (1988). ''The Pink Triangle: The Nazi War Against Homosexuals''. Owl Books. {{ISBN|0-8050-0600-1}}.\n* [http://www.historyplace.com/worldwa